@GDScript.name: @GDScript
@GDScript.description: This contains the list of built-in gdscript functions. Mostly math functions and other utilities. Everything else is expanded by objects.

methods.name: Color8
methods.description: Make a color from red, green, blue and alpha. Arguments can range from 0 to 255.

methods.name: abs
methods.description: Returns the absolute value of parameter s  (i.e. unsigned value, works for integer and float).

methods.name: acos
methods.description: Returns the principal value of the arc cosine of s, expressed in radians. In trigonometrics, arc cosine is the inverse operation of cosine.

methods.name: asin
methods.description: Returns the principal value of the arc sine of s, expressed in radians. In trigonometrics, arc sine is the inverse operation of sine.

methods.name: assert
methods.description: Assert that the condition is true. If the condition is false, generates an error.

methods.name: atan
methods.description: Returns the principal value of the arc tangent of s, expressed in radians. In trigonometrics, arc tangent is the inverse operation of tangent. Notice that because of the sign ambiguity, the function cannot determine with certainty in which quadrant the angle falls only by its tangent value. See [method atan2] for an alternative that takes a fractional argument instead.

methods.name: atan2
methods.description: Returns the principal value of the arc tangent of y/x, expressed in radians. To compute the value, the function takes into account the sign of both arguments in order to determine the quadrant.

methods.name: bytes2var
methods.description: Decode a byte array back to a value.

methods.name: ceil
methods.description: Rounds s upward, returning the smallest integral value that is not less than s.

methods.name: clamp
methods.description: Clamps a value between a minimum and maximum value.

methods.name: convert
methods.description: Convert from a type to another in the best way possible. The "type" parameter uses the enum TYPE_* in [@Global Scope].

methods.name: cos
methods.description: Returns the cosine of an angle of s radians.

methods.name: cosh
methods.description: Returns the hyperbolic cosine of s.

methods.name: db2linear
methods.description: Convert from decibels to linear energy (audio).

methods.name: decimals
methods.description: Return the amount of decimals in the floating point value.

methods.name: dectime
methods.description: Decreases time by a specified amount.

methods.name: deg2rad
methods.description: Convert from degrees to radians.

methods.name: dict2inst
methods.description: Convert a previously converted instances to dictionary back into an instance. Useful for deserializing.

methods.name: ease
methods.description: Easing function, based on exponent. 0 is constant, 1 is linear, 0 to 1 is ease-in, 1+ is ease out. Negative values are in-out/out in.

methods.name: exp
methods.description: Returns the base-e exponential function of s, which is e raised to the power s: e^s.

methods.name: floor
methods.description: Rounds s downward, returning the largest integral value that is not greater than s.

methods.name: fmod
methods.description:
Returns the floating-point remainder of x/y (rounded towards zero):
				[codeblock]
				fmod = x - tquot * y
				[/codeblock]
				Where tquot is the truncated (i.e., rounded towards zero) result of: x/y.

methods.name: fposmod
methods.description: Module (remainder of x/y) that wraps equally in positive and negative.

methods.name: funcref
methods.description: Return a reference to the specified function.

methods.name: hash
methods.description: Hash the variable passed and return an integer.

methods.name: inst2dict
methods.description: Convert a script class instance to a dictionary (useful for serializing).

methods.name: instance_from_id
methods.description: Get an object by its ID.

methods.name: is_inf
methods.description: Returns whether s is an infinity value (either positive infinity or negative infinity).

methods.name: is_nan
methods.description: Returns whether s is a NaN (Not-A-Number) value.

methods.name: lerp
methods.description: Linear interpolates between two values by a normalized value.

methods.name: linear2db
methods.description: Convert from linear energy to decibels (audio).

methods.name: load
methods.description: Load a resource from the filesystem, pass a valid path as argument.

methods.name: log
methods.description: Natural logarithm.

methods.name: max
methods.description: Return the maximum of two values.

methods.name: min
methods.description: Return the minimum of two values.

methods.name: nearest_po2
methods.description: Return the nearest larger power of 2 for an integer.

methods.name: parse_json
methods.description:
Parse JSON text to a Variant (use [method typeof] to check if it is what you expect).
				Be aware that the JSON specification does not define integer or float types, but only a number type. Therefore, parsing a JSON text will convert every numerical values to [float] types.

methods.name: pow
methods.description: Power function, x elevate to y.

methods.name: preload
methods.description: Preload a resource from the filesystem. The resource is loaded during script parsing.

methods.name: print
methods.description: Print one or more arguments to strings in the best way possible to a console line.

methods.name: print_stack
methods.description: Print a stack track at code location, only works when running with debugger turned on.

methods.name: printerr
methods.description: Print one or more arguments to strings in the best way possible to standard error line.

methods.name: printraw
methods.description: Print one or more arguments to strings in the best way possible to console. No newline is added at the end.

methods.name: prints
methods.description: Print one or more arguments to the console with a space between each argument.

methods.name: printt
methods.description: Print one or more arguments to the console with a tab between each argument.

methods.name: rad2deg
methods.description: Convert from radians to degrees.

methods.name: rand_range
methods.description: Random range, any floating point value between 'from' and 'to'.

methods.name: rand_seed
methods.description: Random from seed: pass a seed, and an array with both number and new seed is returned. "Seed" here refers to the internal state of the pseudo random number generator. The internal state of the current implementation is 64 bits.

methods.name: randf
methods.description: Return a random floating point value between 0 and 1.

methods.name: randi
methods.description: Return a random 32 bits integer value. To obtain a random value between 0 to N (where N is smaller than 2^32 - 1), you can use remainder. For example, to get a random integer between 0 and 19 inclusive, you can use randi() % 20.

methods.name: randomize
methods.description: Randomize the seed (or the internal state) of the random number generator. Current implementation reseeds using a number based on time.

methods.name: range
methods.description: Return an array with the given range. Range can be 1 argument N (0 to N-1), two arguments (initial, final-1) or three arguments (initial, final-1, increment).

methods.name: round
methods.description: Returns the integral value that is nearest to s, with halfway cases rounded away from zero.

methods.name: seed
methods.description: Set seed for the random number generator.

methods.name: sign
methods.description: Return sign (-1 or +1).

methods.name: sin
methods.description: Returns the sine of an angle of s radians.

methods.name: sinh
methods.description: Returns the hyperbolic sine of s.

methods.name: sqrt
methods.description: Returns the square root of s.

methods.name: stepify
methods.description: Snap float value to a given step.

methods.name: str
methods.description: Convert one or more arguments to string in the best way possible.

methods.name: str2var
methods.description: Convert a formatted string that was returned by [method var2str] to the original value.

methods.name: tan
methods.description: Returns the tangent of an angle of s radians.

methods.name: tanh
methods.description: Returns the hyperbolic tangent of s.

methods.name: to_json
methods.description: Convert a Variant to json text.

methods.name: typeof
methods.description: Return the internal type of the given Variant object, using the TYPE_* enum in [@Global Scope].

methods.name: validate_json
methods.description: This method is used to validate the structure and data types of a piece of JSON, similar to XML Schema for XML.

methods.name: var2bytes
methods.description: Encode a variable value to a byte array.

methods.name: var2str
methods.description: Convert a value to a formatted string that can later be parsed using [method str2var].

methods.name: weakref
methods.description:
Return a weak reference to an object.
				A weak reference to an object is not enough to keep the object alive: when the only remaining references to a referent are weak references, garbage collection is free to destroy the referent and reuse its memory for something else. However, until the object is actually destroyed the weak reference may return the object even if there are no strong references to it.

methods.name: yield
methods.description:
Stop the function execution and return the current state. Call [method GDFunctionState.resume] on the state to resume execution. This invalidates the state.
				Returns anything that was passed to the resume function call. If passed an object and a signal, the execution is resumed when the object's signal is emitted.

constants.name: PI
constants.description: Constant that represents how many times the diameter of a circumference fits around its perimeter.

constants.name: INF
constants.description: A positive infinity. (For negative infinity, use -INF).

constants.name: NAN
constants.description:
Macro constant that expands to an expression of type float that represents a NaN.
			The NaN values are used to identify undefined or non-representable values for floating-point elements, such as the square root of negative numbers or the result of 0/0.

@Global Scope.name: @Global Scope
@Global Scope.description:
Global scope constants and variables. This is all that resides in the globals, constants regarding error codes, scancodes, property hints, etc. It's not much.
		Singletons are also documented here, since they can be accessed from anywhere.

constants.name: MARGIN_LEFT
constants.description: Left margin, used usually for [Control] or [StyleBox] derived classes.

constants.name: MARGIN_TOP
constants.description: Top margin, used usually for [Control] or [StyleBox] derived classes.

constants.name: MARGIN_RIGHT
constants.description: Right margin, used usually for [Control] or [StyleBox] derived classes.

constants.name: MARGIN_BOTTOM
constants.description: Bottom margin, used usually for [Control] or [StyleBox] derived classes.

constants.name: VERTICAL
constants.description: General vertical alignment, used usually for [Separator], [ScrollBar], [Slider], etc.

constants.name: HORIZONTAL
constants.description: General horizontal alignment, used usually for [Separator], [ScrollBar], [Slider], etc.

constants.name: HALIGN_LEFT
constants.description: Horizontal left alignment, usually for text-derived classes.

constants.name: HALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Horizontal center alignment, usually for text-derived classes.

constants.name: HALIGN_RIGHT
constants.description: Horizontal right alignment, usually for text-derived classes.

constants.name: VALIGN_TOP
constants.description: Vertical top alignment, usually for text-derived classes.

constants.name: VALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Vertical center alignment, usually for text-derived classes.

constants.name: VALIGN_BOTTOM
constants.description: Vertical bottom alignment, usually for text-derived classes.

constants.name: SPKEY
constants.description: Scancodes with this bit applied are non printable.

constants.name: OK
constants.description: Functions that return Error return OK when everything went ok. Most functions don't return error anyway and/or just print errors to stdout.

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_RANGE
constants.description: Hints that the string is a range, defined as "min,max" or "min,max,step". This is valid for integers and floats.

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_EXP_RANGE
constants.description: Hints that the string is an exponential range, defined as "min,max" or "min,max,step". This is valid for integers and floats.

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_ENUM
constants.description: Property hint for an enumerated value, like "Hello,Something,Else". This is valid for integer, float and string properties.

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_FLAGS
constants.description: Property hint for a bitmask description, for bits 0,1,2,3 and 5 the hint would be like "Bit0,Bit1,Bit2,Bit3,,Bit5". Valid only for integers.

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_FILE
constants.description: String property is a file (so pop up a file dialog when edited). Hint string can be a set of wildcards like "*.doc".

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_DIR
constants.description: String property is a directory (so pop up a file dialog when edited).

constants.name: PROPERTY_HINT_RESOURCE_TYPE
constants.description: String property is a resource, so open the resource popup menu when edited.

constants.name: PROPERTY_USAGE_STORAGE
constants.description: Property will be used as storage (default).

constants.name: PROPERTY_USAGE_EDITOR
constants.description: Property will be visible in editor (default).

constants.name: TYPE_NIL
constants.description: Variable is of type nil (only applied for null).

AStar.name: AStar
AStar.brief_description: AStar class representation that uses vectors as edges.
AStar.description:
A* (A star) is a computer algorithm that is widely used in pathfinding and graph traversal, the process of plotting an efficiently directed path between multiple points. It enjoys widespread use due to its performance and accuracy. Godot's A* implementation make use of vectors as points.
		You must add points manually with [method AStar.add_point] and create segments manually with [method AStar.connect_points]. So you can test if there is a path between two points with the [method AStar.are_points_connected] function, get the list of existing ids in the found path with [method AStar.get_id_path], or the points list with [method AStar.get_point_path].

methods.name: add_point
methods.description: Add a new point at the given position [code]pos[/code] with the given identifier [code]id[/code]. The [code]weight_scale[/code] has to be 1 or larger.

methods.name: are_points_connected
methods.description: Returns if there is a connection/segment between points [code]id[/code] and [code]from_id[/code]

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear all the points and segments from AStar instance.

methods.name: connect_points
methods.description: Create a segment between points [code]id[/code] and [code]to_id[/code].

methods.name: disconnect_points
methods.description: Deletes a segment between points [code]id[/code] and [code]to_id[/code].

methods.name: get_closest_point
methods.description: Returns the id of closest point of given point.  -1 is returned if there are no points on AStar.

methods.name: get_closest_pos_in_segment
methods.description: Returns the position of closest point that has segments.

methods.name: get_id_path
methods.description: Returns an array with the point ids of path found by AStar between two given points.

methods.name: get_point_path
methods.description: Returns an array with the points of path found by AStar between two given points.

methods.name: get_point_pos
methods.description: Returns the position of point with given id.

methods.name: get_point_weight_scale
methods.description: Returns the weight scale of point with given id.

methods.name: has_point
methods.description: Returns if the point with given id exists on AStar;

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Removes the point with given id.

AcceptDialog.name: AcceptDialog
AcceptDialog.description: This dialog is useful for small notifications to the user about an event. It can only be accepted or closed, with the same result.

methods.name: add_button
methods.description:
Add custom button to the dialog and return the created button.
				The button titled with [i]text[/i] and the [i]action[/i] will be passed to [custom_action] signal when it is pressed.

methods.name: add_cancel
methods.description: Add custom cancel button to the dialog and return the created button.

methods.name: get_hide_on_ok
methods.description: Return true if the dialog will be hidden when accepted (default true).

methods.name: get_label
methods.description: Return the label used for built-in text.

methods.name: get_ok
methods.description: Return the OK Button.

methods.name: get_text
methods.description: Return the built-in label text.

methods.name: register_text_enter
methods.description: Register a [LineEdit] in the dialog. When the enter key is pressed, the dialog will be accepted.

methods.name: set_hide_on_ok
methods.description: Set whether the dialog is hidden when accepted (default true).

methods.name: set_text
methods.description: Set the built-in label text.

signals.name: confirmed
signals.description: Emitted when accepted.

signals.name: custom_action
signals.description: Emitted with a custom button is added.

AnimatedSprite.name: AnimatedSprite
AnimatedSprite.brief_description: Sprite node that can use multiple textures for animation.
AnimatedSprite.description: Sprite node that can use multiple textures for animation.

methods.name: get_animation
methods.description: Return the name of the current animation set to the node.

methods.name: get_frame
methods.description: Return the visible frame index.

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Return the offset of the sprite in the node origin.

methods.name: get_sprite_frames
methods.description: Get the [SpriteFrames] resource, which contains all frames.

methods.name: is_centered
methods.description: Return true when centered. See [method set_centered].

methods.name: is_flipped_h
methods.description: Return true if sprite is flipped horizontally.

methods.name: is_flipped_v
methods.description: Return true if sprite is flipped vertically.

methods.name: is_playing
methods.description: Return true if an animation if currently being played.

methods.name: play
methods.description: Play the animation set in parameter. If no parameter is provided, the current animation is played.

methods.name: set_animation
methods.description: Set the current animation of the node and reinits the frame counter of the animation.

methods.name: set_centered
methods.description: When turned on, offset at (0,0) is the center of the sprite, when off, the top-left corner is.

methods.name: set_flip_h
methods.description: If true, sprite is flipped horizontally.

methods.name: set_flip_v
methods.description: If true, sprite is flipped vertically.

methods.name: set_frame
methods.description: Set the visible sprite frame index (from the list of frames inside the [SpriteFrames] resource).

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Set the offset of the sprite in the node origin. Position varies depending on whether it is centered or not.

methods.name: set_sprite_frames
methods.description: Set the [SpriteFrames] resource, which contains all frames.

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stop the current animation (does not reset the frame counter).

signals.name: animation_finished
signals.description: Emitted when the animation is finished (when it plays the last frame). If the animation is looping, this signal is emitted every time the last frame is drawn, before looping.

signals.name: frame_changed
signals.description: Emitted when frame is changed.

methods.name: get_animation
methods.description: Return the name of the current animation set to the node.

methods.name: get_frame
methods.description: Return the visible frame index.

methods.name: get_sprite_frames
methods.description: Get the [SpriteFrames] resource, which contains all frames.

methods.name: is_playing
methods.description: Return true if an animation if currently being played.

methods.name: play
methods.description: Play the animation set in parameter. If no parameter is provided, the current animation is played.

methods.name: set_animation
methods.description: Set the current animation of the node and reinits the frame counter of the animation.

methods.name: set_frame
methods.description: Set the visible sprite frame index (from the list of frames inside the [SpriteFrames] resource).

methods.name: set_sprite_frames
methods.description: Set the [SpriteFrames] resource, which contains all frames.

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stop the current animation (does not reset the frame counter).

signals.name: frame_changed
signals.description: Emitted when frame is changed.

Animation.name: Animation
Animation.brief_description: Contains data used to animate everything in the engine.
Animation.description:
An Animation resource contains data used to animate everything in the engine. Animations are divided into tracks, and each track must be linked to a node. The state of that node can be changed through time, by adding timed keys (events) to the track.
		Animations are just data containers, and must be added to odes such as an [AnimationPlayer] or [AnimationTreePlayer] to be played back.

methods.name: add_track
methods.description: Add a track to the Animation. The track type must be specified as any of the values in the TYPE_* enumeration.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the animation (clear all tracks and reset all).

methods.name: find_track
methods.description: Return the index of the specified track. If the track is not found, return -1.

methods.name: get_length
methods.description: Return the total length of the animation (in seconds).

methods.name: get_step
methods.description: Get the animation step value.

methods.name: get_track_count
methods.description: Return the amount of tracks in the animation.

methods.name: has_loop
methods.description: Return whether the animation has the loop flag set.

methods.name: method_track_get_key_indices
methods.description: Return all the key indices of a method track, given a position and delta time.

methods.name: method_track_get_name
methods.description: Return the method name of a method track.

methods.name: method_track_get_params
methods.description: Return the arguments values to be called on a method track for a given key in a given track.

methods.name: remove_track
methods.description: Remove a track by specifying the track index.

methods.name: set_length
methods.description: Set the total length of the animation (in seconds). Note that length is not delimited by the last key, as this one may be before or after the end to ensure correct interpolation and looping.

methods.name: set_loop
methods.description: Set a flag indicating that the animation must loop. This is uses for correct interpolation of animation cycles, and for hinting the player that it must restart the animation.

methods.name: set_step
methods.description: Set the animation step value.

methods.name: track_find_key
methods.description: Find the key index by time in a given track. Optionally, only find it if the exact time is given.

methods.name: track_get_interpolation_type
methods.description: Return the interpolation type of a given track, from the INTERPOLATION_* enum.

methods.name: track_get_key_count
methods.description: Return the amount of keys in a given track.

methods.name: track_get_key_time
methods.description: Return the time at which the key is located.

methods.name: track_get_key_transition
methods.description: Return the transition curve (easing) for a specific key (see built-in math function "ease").

methods.name: track_get_key_value
methods.description: Return the value of a given key in a given track.

methods.name: track_get_path
methods.description: Get the path of a track. for more information on the path format, see [method track_set_path]

methods.name: track_get_type
methods.description: Get the type of a track.

methods.name: track_insert_key
methods.description: Insert a generic key in a given track.

methods.name: track_is_imported
methods.description: Return true if the given track is imported. Else, return false.

methods.name: track_move_down
methods.description: Move a track down.

methods.name: track_move_up
methods.description: Move a track up.

methods.name: track_remove_key
methods.description: Remove a key by index in a given track.

methods.name: track_remove_key_at_pos
methods.description: Remove a key by position (seconds) in a given track.

methods.name: track_set_imported
methods.description: Set the given track as imported or not.

methods.name: track_set_interpolation_type
methods.description: Set the interpolation type of a given track, from the INTERPOLATION_* enum.

methods.name: track_set_key_transition
methods.description: Set the transition curve (easing) for a specific key (see built-in math function "ease").

methods.name: track_set_key_value
methods.description: Set the value of an existing key.

methods.name: track_set_path
methods.description: Set the path of a track. Paths must be valid scene-tree paths to a node, and must be specified starting from the parent node of the node that will reproduce the animation. Tracks that control properties or bones must append their name after the path, separated by ":". Example: "character/skeleton:ankle" or "character/mesh:transform/local"

methods.name: transform_track_insert_key
methods.description: Insert a transform key for a transform track.

methods.name: transform_track_interpolate
methods.description: Return the interpolated value of a transform track at a given time (in seconds). An array consisting of 3 elements: position ([Vector3]), rotation ([Quat]) and scale ([Vector3]).

methods.name: value_track_get_key_indices
methods.description: Return all the key indices of a value track, given a position and delta time.

constants.name: TYPE_VALUE
constants.description: Value tracks set values in node properties, but only those which can be Interpolated.

constants.name: TYPE_TRANSFORM
constants.description: Transform tracks are used to change node local transforms or skeleton pose bones. Transitions are Interpolated.

constants.name: TYPE_METHOD
constants.description: Method tracks call functions with given arguments per key.

AnimationPlayer.name: AnimationPlayer
AnimationPlayer.description: An animation player is used for general purpose playback of [Animation] resources. It contains a dictionary of animations (referenced by name) and custom blend times between their transitions. Additionally, animations can be played and blended in different channels.

methods.name: add_animation
methods.description: Add an animation resource to the player, which will be later referenced by the "name" argument.

methods.name: advance
methods.description: Used to skip ahead or skip back in an animation. Delta is the time in seconds to skip.

methods.name: clear_caches
methods.description: The animation player creates caches for faster access to the nodes it will animate. However, if a specific node is removed, it may not notice it, so clear_caches will force the player to search for the nodes again.

methods.name: clear_queue
methods.description: If animations are queued to play, clear them.

methods.name: find_animation
methods.description: Find an animation name by resource.

methods.name: get_animation
methods.description: Get an [Animation] resource by requesting a name.

methods.name: get_animation_list
methods.description: Get the list of names of the animations stored in the player.

methods.name: get_animation_process_mode
methods.description: Return the mode in which the animation player processes. See [method set_animation_process_mode].

methods.name: get_autoplay
methods.description: Return the name of the animation that will be automatically played when the scene is loaded.

methods.name: get_blend_time
methods.description: Get the blend time between two animations, referenced by their names.

methods.name: get_current_animation
methods.description: Return the name of the animation being played.

methods.name: get_current_animation_length
methods.description: Get the length (in seconds) of the currently being played animation.

methods.name: get_current_animation_pos
methods.description: Get the position (in seconds) of the currently being played animation.

methods.name: get_default_blend_time
methods.description: Return the default blend time between animations.

methods.name: get_pos
methods.description: Return the playback position (in seconds) in an animation channel (or channel 0 if none is provided).

methods.name: get_root
methods.description: Return path to root node (see [method set_root]).

methods.name: get_speed_scale
methods.description: Get the speed scaling ratio in a given animation channel (or channel 0 if none is provided). Default ratio is [i]1[/i] (no scaling).

methods.name: has_animation
methods.description: Request whether an [Animation] name exist within the player.

methods.name: is_active
methods.description: Return true if the player is active.

methods.name: is_playing
methods.description: Return whether an animation is playing.

methods.name: play
methods.description: Play a given animation by the animation name. Custom speed and blend times can be set. If custom speed is negative (-1), 'from_end' being true can play the animation backwards.

methods.name: play_backwards
methods.description: Play a given animation by the animation name in reverse.

methods.name: queue
methods.description: Queue an animation for playback once the current one is done.

methods.name: remove_animation
methods.description: Remove an animation from the player (by supplying the same name used to add it).

methods.name: rename_animation
methods.description: Rename an existing animation.

methods.name: seek
methods.description: Seek the animation to a given position in time (in seconds). If 'update' is true, the animation will be updated too, otherwise it will be updated at process time.

methods.name: set_active
methods.description: Set the player as active (playing). If false, it will do nothing.

methods.name: set_animation_process_mode
methods.description: Set the mode in which the animation player processes. By default, it processes on idle time (framerate dependent), but using fixed time works well for animating static collision bodies in 2D and 3D. See enum ANIMATION_PROCESS_*.

methods.name: set_autoplay
methods.description: Set the name of the animation that will be automatically played when the scene is loaded.

methods.name: set_blend_time
methods.description: Specify a blend time (in seconds) between two animations, referenced by their names.

methods.name: set_current_animation
methods.description: Set the current animation (even if no playback occurs). Using set_current_animation() and set_active() are similar to calling play().

methods.name: set_default_blend_time
methods.description: Set the default blend time between animations.

methods.name: set_root

Area.name: Area
Area.brief_description: General purpose area detection and influence for 3D physics.
Area.description: General purpose area detection for 3D physics. Areas can be used for detection of objects that enter/exit them, as well as overriding space parameters (changing gravity, damping, etc). For this, use any space override different from AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLE and point gravity at the center of mass.

methods.name: get_angular_damp
methods.description: Return the angular damp rate.

methods.name: get_collision_layer
methods.description: Return the physics layer this area is in.

methods.name: get_collision_layer_bit
methods.description: Return an individual bit on the layer mask.

methods.name: get_collision_mask
methods.description: Return the physics layers this area can scan for collisions.

methods.name: get_collision_mask_bit
methods.description: Return an individual bit on the collision mask.

methods.name: get_gravity
methods.description: Return the gravity intensity.

methods.name: get_gravity_distance_scale
methods.description: Return the falloff factor for point gravity.

methods.name: get_gravity_vector
methods.description: Return the gravity vector. If gravity is a point (see [method is_gravity_a_point]), this will be the attraction center.

methods.name: get_linear_damp
methods.description: Return the linear damp rate.

methods.name: get_overlapping_areas
methods.description: Return a list of the areas that are totally or partially inside this area.

methods.name: get_overlapping_bodies
methods.description: Return a list of the bodies ([PhysicsBody]) that are totally or partially inside this area.

methods.name: get_priority
methods.description: Return the processing order of this area.

methods.name: get_space_override_mode
methods.description: Return the space override mode.

methods.name: is_gravity_a_point
methods.description: Return whether gravity is a point. A point gravity will attract objects towards it, as opposed to a gravity vector, which moves them in a given direction.

methods.name: is_monitorable
methods.description: Return whether this area can be detected by other, monitoring, areas.

methods.name: is_monitoring
methods.description: Return whether this area detects bodies/areas entering/exiting it.

methods.name: overlaps_area
methods.description: Return whether the area passed is totally or partially inside this area.

methods.name: overlaps_body
methods.description: Return whether the body passed is totally or partially inside this area.

methods.name: set_angular_damp
methods.description:
Set the rate at which objects stop spinning in this area, if there are not any other forces making it spin. The value is a fraction of its current speed, lost per second. Thus, a value of 1.0 should mean stopping immediately, and 0.0 means the object never stops.
				In practice, as the fraction of speed lost gets smaller with each frame, a value of 1.0 does not mean the object will stop in exactly one second. Only when the physics calculations are done at 1 frame per second, it does stop in a second.

methods.name: set_collision_layer
methods.description:
Set the physics layers this area is in.
				Collidable objects can exist in any of 32 different layers. These layers are not visual, but more of a tagging system instead. A collidable can use these layers/tags to select with which objects it can collide, using [method set_collision_mask].
				A contact is detected if object A is in any of the layers that object B scans, or object B is in any layer scanned by object A.

methods.name: set_collision_layer_bit
methods.description: Set/clear individual bits on the layer mask. This makes getting an area in/out of only one layer easier.

methods.name: set_collision_mask
methods.description: Set the physics layers this area can scan for collisions.

methods.name: set_collision_mask_bit
methods.description: Set/clear individual bits on the collision mask. This makes selecting the areas scanned easier.

methods.name: set_gravity
methods.description:
Set the gravity intensity. This is useful to alter the force of gravity without altering its direction.
				This value multiplies the gravity vector, whether it is the given vector ([method set_gravity_vector]), or a calculated one (when using a center of gravity).

methods.name: set_gravity_distance_scale
methods.description: Set the falloff factor for point gravity. The greater this value is, the faster the strength of gravity decreases with the square of distance.

methods.name: set_gravity_is_point
methods.description: When overriding space parameters, this method sets whether this area has a center of gravity. To set/get the location of the center of gravity, use [method set_gravity_vector]/[method get_gravity_vector].

methods.name: set_gravity_vector
methods.description:
Set the gravity vector. This vector does not have to be normalized.
				If gravity is a point (see [method is_gravity_a_point]), this will be the attraction center.

methods.name: set_linear_damp
methods.description:
Set the rate at which objects stop moving in this area, if there are not any other forces moving it. The value is a fraction of its current speed, lost per second. Thus, a value of 1.0 should mean stopping immediately, and 0.0 means the object never stops.
				In practice, as the fraction of speed lost gets smaller with each frame, a value of 1.0 does not mean the object will stop in exactly one second. Only when the physics calculations are done at 1 frame per second, it does stop in a second.

methods.name: set_monitorable
methods.description: Set whether this area can be detected by other, monitoring, areas. Only areas need to be marked as monitorable. Bodies are always so.

methods.name: set_monitoring
methods.description: Set whether this area can detect bodies/areas entering/exiting it.

methods.name: set_priority
methods.description:
Set the order in which the area is processed. Greater values mean the area gets processed first. This is useful for areas which have an space override different from AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLED or AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE, as they replace values, and are thus order-dependent.
				Areas with the same priority value get evaluated in an unpredictable order, and should be differentiated if evaluation order is to be important.

methods.name: set_space_override_mode
methods.description:
Set the space override mode. This mode controls how an area affects gravity and damp.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLED: This area does not affect gravity/damp. These are generally areas that exist only to detect collisions, and objects entering or exiting them.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE: This area adds its gravity/damp values to whatever has been calculated so far. This way, many overlapping areas can combine their physics to make interesting effects.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE_REPLACE: This area adds its gravity/damp values to whatever has been calculated so far. Then stops taking into account the rest of the areas, even the default one.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE: This area replaces any gravity/damp, even the default one, and stops taking into account the rest of the areas.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE_COMBINE: This area replaces any gravity/damp calculated so far, but keeps calculating the rest of the areas, down to the default one.

signals.name: area_entered
signals.description: This signal is triggered only once when an area enters this area. The only parameter passed is the area that entered this area.

signals.name: area_exited
signals.description: This signal is triggered only once when an area exits this area. The only parameter passed is the area that exited this area.

signals.name: area_shape_entered
signals.description: This signal triggers only once when an area enters this area. The first parameter is the area's [RID]. The second one is the area as an object. The third one is the index of the shape entering this area, and the fourth one is the index of the shape in this area that reported the entering.

signals.name: area_shape_exited
signals.description: This signal triggers only once when an area exits this area. The first parameter is the area's [RID]. The second one is the area as an object. The third one is the index of the shape entering this area, and the fourth one is the index of the shape in this area that reported the entering.

signals.name: body_entered
signals.description: This signal is triggered only once when a body enters this area. The only parameter passed is the body that entered this area.

signals.name: body_exited
signals.description: This signal is triggered only once when a body exits this area. The only parameter passed is the body that exited this area.

signals.name: body_shape_entered
signals.description: This signal triggers only once when a body enters this area. The first parameter is the body's [RID]. The second one is the body as an object. The third one is the index of the shape of the body that entered this area, and the fourth one is the index of the shape in this area that reported the entering.

signals.name: body_shape_exited
signals.description: This signal triggers only once when a body exits this area. The first parameter is the body's [RID]. The second one is the body as an object. The third one is the index of the shape exiting this area, and the fourth one is the index of the shape in this area that reported the exit.
