ConvexPolygonShape.name: ConvexPolygonShape
ConvexPolygonShape.description: Convex polygon shape resource, which can be set into a [PhysicsBody] or area.

ConvexPolygonShape2D.name: ConvexPolygonShape2D
ConvexPolygonShape2D.description:
Convex Polygon Shape for 2D physics. A convex polygon, whatever its shape, is internally decomposed into as many convex polygons as needed to ensure all collision checks against it are always done on convex polygons (which are faster to check).
		The main difference between a [ConvexPolygonShape2D] and a [ConcavePolygonShape2D] is that a concave polygon assumes it is concave and uses a more complex method of collision detection, and a convex one forces itself to be convex in order to speed up collision detection.

methods.name: get_points
methods.description: Return a list of points in either clockwise or counter clockwise order, forming a convex polygon.

methods.name: set_point_cloud
methods.description: Currently, this method does nothing.

methods.name: set_points
methods.description: Set a list of points in either clockwise or counter clockwise order, forming a convex polygon.

Curve2D.name: Curve2D
Curve2D.brief_description: Describes a Bezier curve in 2D space.
Curve2D.description:
This class describes a Bezier curve in 2D space. It is mainly used to give a shape to a [Path2D], but can be manually sampled for other purposes.
		It keeps a cache of precalculated points along the curve, to speed further calculations up.

methods.name: add_point
methods.description:
Adds a point to a curve, at position "pos", with control points "in" and "out".
				If "atpos" is given, the point is inserted before the point number "atpos", moving that point (and every point after) after the inserted point. If "atpos" is not given, or is an illegal value (atpos <0 or atpos >= [method get_point_count]), the point will be appended at the end of the point list.

methods.name: get_bake_interval
methods.description: Returns the distance between two adjacent cached points.

methods.name: get_baked_length
methods.description: Returns the total length of the curve, based on the cached points. Given enough density (see [method set_bake_interval]), it should be approximate enough.

methods.name: get_baked_points
methods.description: Returns the cache of points as a [PoolVector2Array].

methods.name: get_point_count
methods.description: Returns the number of points describing the curve.

methods.name: get_point_in
methods.description: Returns the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_out
methods.description: Returns the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_pos
methods.description: Returns the position of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0).

methods.name: interpolate
methods.description:
Returns the position between the vertex "idx" and the vertex "idx"+1, where "t" controls if the point is the first vertex (t = 0.0), the last vertex (t = 1.0), or in between. Values of "t" outside the range (0.0 >= t  <=1) give strange, but predictable results.
				If "idx" is out of bounds it is truncated to the first or last vertex, and "t" is ignored. If the curve has no points, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0).

methods.name: interpolate_baked
methods.description:
Returns a point within the curve at position "offset", where "offset" is measured as a pixel distance along the curve.
				To do that, it finds the two cached points where the "offset" lies between, then interpolates the values. This interpolation is cubic if "cubic" is set to true, or linear if set to false.
				Cubic interpolation tends to follow the curves better, but linear is faster (and often, precise enough).

methods.name: interpolatef
methods.description: Returns the position at the vertex "fofs". It calls [method interpolate] using the integer part of fofs as "idx", and its fractional part as "t".

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Deletes the point "idx" from the curve. Sends an error to the console if "idx" is out of bounds.

methods.name: set_bake_interval
methods.description: Sets the distance in pixels between two adjacent cached points. Changing it forces the cache to be recomputed the next time a xxx_baked_xxx function is called. The less distance, the more points the cache will have, and the more memory it will consume, so use with care.

methods.name: set_point_in
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_out
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_pos
methods.description: Sets the position for the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: tesselate
methods.description:
Returns a list of points along the curve, with a curvature controlled point density. That is, the curvier parts will have more points than the straighter parts.
				This approximation makes straight segments between each point, then subdivides those segments until the resulting shape is similar enough.
				"max_stages" controls how many subdivisions a curve segment may face before it is considered approximate enough. Each subdivision splits the segment in half, so the default 5 stages may mean up to 32 subdivisions per curve segment. Increase with care!
				"tolerance_degrees" controls how many degrees the midpoint of a segment may deviate from the real curve, before the segment has to be subdivided.

Curve3D.name: Curve3D
Curve3D.brief_description: Describes a Bezier curve in 3D space.
Curve3D.description:
This class describes a Bezier curve in 3D space. It is mainly used to give a shape to a [Path], but can be manually sampled for other purposes.
		It keeps a cache of precalculated points along the curve, to speed further calculations up.

methods.name: add_point
methods.description:
Adds a point to a curve, at position "pos", with control points "in" and "out".
				If "atpos" is given, the point is inserted before the point number "atpos", moving that point (and every point after) after the inserted point. If "atpos" is not given, or is an illegal value (atpos <0 or atpos >= [method get_point_count]), the point will be appended at the end of the point list.

methods.name: get_bake_interval
methods.description: Returns the distance between two adjacent cached points.

methods.name: get_baked_length
methods.description: Returns the total length of the curve, based on the cached points. Given enough density (see [method set_bake_interval]), it should be approximate enough.

methods.name: get_baked_points
methods.description: Returns the cache of points as a [PoolVector3Array].

methods.name: get_baked_tilts
methods.description: Returns the cache of tilts as a [RealArray].

methods.name: get_point_count
methods.description: Returns the number of points describing the curve.

methods.name: get_point_in
methods.description: Returns the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_out
methods.description: Returns the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_pos
methods.description: Returns the position of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_tilt
methods.description: Returns the tilt angle in radians for the point "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns 0.

methods.name: interpolate
methods.description:
Returns the position between the vertex "idx" and the vertex "idx"+1, where "t" controls if the point is the first vertex (t = 0.0), the last vertex (t = 1.0), or in between. Values of "t" outside the range (0.0 >= t  <=1) give strange, but predictable results.
				If "idx" is out of bounds it is truncated to the first or last vertex, and "t" is ignored. If the curve has no points, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: interpolate_baked
methods.description:
Returns a point within the curve at position "offset", where "offset" is measured as a distance in 3D units along the curve.
				To do that, it finds the two cached points where the "offset" lies between, then interpolates the values. This interpolation is cubic if "cubic" is set to true, or linear if set to false.
				Cubic interpolation tends to follow the curves better, but linear is faster (and often, precise enough).

methods.name: interpolatef
methods.description: Returns the position at the vertex "fofs". It calls [method interpolate] using the integer part of fofs as "idx", and its fractional part as "t".

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Deletes the point "idx" from the curve. Sends an error to the console if "idx" is out of bounds.

methods.name: set_bake_interval
methods.description: Sets the distance in 3D units between two adjacent cached points. Changing it forces the cache to be recomputed the next time a xxx_baked_xxx function is called. The less distance, the more points the cache will have, and the more memory it will consume, so use with care.

methods.name: set_point_in
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_out
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_pos
methods.description: Sets the position for the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_tilt
methods.description:
Sets the tilt angle in radians for the point "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.
				The tilt controls the rotation along the look-at axis an object traveling the path would have. In the case of a curve controlling a [PathFollow], this tilt is an offset over the natural tilt the PathFollow calculates.

methods.name: tesselate
methods.description:
Returns a list of points along the curve, with a curvature controlled point density. That is, the curvier parts will have more points than the straighter parts.
				This approximation makes straight segments between each point, then subdivides those segments until the resulting shape is similar enough.
				"max_stages" controls how many subdivisions a curve segment may face before it is considered approximate enough. Each subdivision splits the segment in half, so the default 5 stages may mean up to 32 subdivisions per curve segment. Increase with care!
				"tolerance_degrees" controls how many degrees the midpoint of a segment may deviate from the real curve, before the segment has to be subdivided.

DampedSpringJoint2D.name: DampedSpringJoint2D
DampedSpringJoint2D.description: Damped spring constraint for 2D physics. This resembles a spring joint that always wants to go back to a given length.

methods.name: get_damping
methods.description: Return the damping ratio of the spring joint. A value of 0 indicates an undamped spring, while 1 causes the system to reach equilibrium as fast as possible (critical damping).

methods.name: get_length
methods.description: Return the maximum length of the spring joint.

methods.name: get_rest_length
methods.description: Return the resting length of the spring joint. The joint will always try to go to back this length when pulled apart.

methods.name: get_stiffness
methods.description: Return the stiffness of the spring joint. The joint applies a force equal to the stiffness times the distance from its resting length.

methods.name: set_damping
methods.description: Set the damping ratio of the spring joint. A value of 0 indicates an undamped spring, while 1 causes the system to reach equilibrium as fast as possible (critical damping).

methods.name: set_length
methods.description: Set the maximum length of the spring joint.

methods.name: set_rest_length
methods.description: Set the resting length of the spring joint. The joint will always try to go to back this length when pulled apart.

methods.name: set_stiffness
methods.description: Set the stiffness of the spring joint. The joint applies a force equal to the stiffness times the distance from its resting length.

Dictionary.name: Dictionary
Dictionary.description: Dictionary type. Associative container which contains values referenced by unique keys. Dictionaries are always passed by reference.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the dictionary, removing all key/value pairs.

methods.name: empty
methods.description: Return true if the dictionary is empty.

methods.name: erase
methods.description: Erase a dictionary key/value pair by key.

methods.name: has
methods.description: Return true if the dictionary has a given key.

methods.name: has_all
methods.description: Return true if the dictionary has all of the keys in the given array.

methods.name: hash
methods.description: Return a hashed integer value representing the dictionary contents.

methods.name: keys
methods.description: Return the list of keys in the [Dictionary].

methods.name: size
methods.description: Return the size of the dictionary (in pairs).

methods.name: values
methods.description: Return the list of values in the [Dictionary].

DirectionalLight.name: DirectionalLight
DirectionalLight.brief_description: Directional Light, such as the Sun or the Moon.
DirectionalLight.description: A DirectionalLight is a type of [Light] node that emits light constantly in one direction (the negative z axis of the node). It is used lights with strong intensity that are located far away from the scene to model sunlight or moonlight. The worldspace location of the DirectionalLight transform (origin) is ignored, only the basis is used do determine light direction.

Directory.name: Directory
Directory.brief_description: Type used to handle the filesystem.

methods.name: change_dir
methods.description:
Change the currently opened directory to the one passed as an argument. The argument can be relative to the current directory (e.g. [code]newdir[/code] or [code]../newdir[/code]), or an absolute path (e.g. [code]/tmp/newdir[/code] or [code]res://somedir/newdir[/code]).
				The method returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or ERR_*).

methods.name: copy
methods.description:
Copy the [i]from[/i] file to the [i]to[/i] destination. Both arguments should be paths to files, either relative or absolute. If the destination file exists and is not access-protected, it will be overwritten.
				Returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK, FAILED or ERR_*).

methods.name: current_is_dir
methods.description: Return whether the current item processed with the last [method get_next] call is a directory ([code].[/code] and [code]..[/code] are considered directories).

methods.name: dir_exists
methods.description: Return whether the target directory exists. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path.

methods.name: file_exists
methods.description: Return whether the target file exists. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path.

methods.name: get_current_dir
methods.description: Return the absolute path to the currently opened directory (e.g. [code]res://folder[/code] or [code]C:\tmp\folder[/code]).

methods.name: get_drive
methods.description: On Windows, return the name of the drive (partition) passed as an argument (e.g. [code]C:[/code]). On other platforms, or if the requested drive does not existed, the method returns an empty String.

methods.name: get_drive_count
methods.description: On Windows, return the number of drives (partitions) mounted on the current filesystem. On other platforms, the method returns 0.

methods.name: get_next
methods.description:
Return the next element (file or directory) in the current directory (including [code].[/code] and [code]..[/code], unless [code]skip_navigational[/code] was given to [method list_dir_begin]).
				The name of the file or directory is returned (and not its full path). Once the stream has been fully processed, the method returns an empty String and closes the stream automatically (i.e. [method list_dir_end] would not be mandatory in such a case).

methods.name: get_space_left
methods.description: On Unix desktop systems, return the available space on the current directory's disk. On other platforms, this information is not available and the method returns 0 or -1.

methods.name: list_dir_begin
methods.description:
Initialise the stream used to list all files and directories using the [method get_next] function, closing the current opened stream if needed. Once the stream has been processed, it should typically be closed with [method list_dir_end].
				If you pass [code]skip_navigational[/code], then [code].[/code] and [code]..[/code] would be filtered out.
				If you pass [code]skip_hidden[/code], then hidden files would be filtered out.

methods.name: list_dir_end
methods.description: Close the current stream opened with [method list_dir_begin] (whether it has been fully processed with [method get_next] or not does not matter).

methods.name: make_dir
methods.description:
Create a directory. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path. The target directory should be placed in an already existing directory (to create the full path recursively, see [method make_dir_recursive]).
				The method returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK, FAILED or ERR_*).

methods.name: make_dir_recursive
methods.description:
Create a target directory and all necessary intermediate directories in its path, by calling [method make_dir] recursively. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path.
				Return one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK, FAILED or ERR_*).

methods.name: open
methods.description:
Open an existing directory of the filesystem. The [i]path[/i] argument can be within the project tree ([code]res://folder[/code]), the user directory ([code]user://folder[/code]) or an absolute path of the user filesystem (e.g. [code]/tmp/folder[/code] or [code]C:\tmp\folder[/code]).
				The method returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or ERR_*).

methods.name: remove
methods.description:
Delete the target file or an empty directory. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path. If the target directory is not empty, the operation will fail.
				Return one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or FAILED).

methods.name: rename
methods.description:
Rename (move) the [i]from[/i] file to the [i]to[/i] destination. Both arguments should be paths to files, either relative or absolute. If the destination file exists and is not access-protected, it will be overwritten.
				Return one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or FAILED).

EditorFileSystem.name: EditorFileSystem
EditorFileSystem.brief_description: Resource filesystem, as the editor sees it.
EditorFileSystem.description: This object holds information of all resources in the filesystem, their types, etc.

methods.name: get_file_type
methods.description: Get the type of the file, given the full path.

methods.name: get_filesystem
methods.description: Get the root directory object.

methods.name: get_scanning_progress
methods.description: Return the scan progress for 0 to 1 if the FS is being scanned.

methods.name: is_scanning
methods.description: Return true of the filesystem is being scanned.

methods.name: scan
methods.description: Scan the filesystem for changes.

methods.name: scan_sources
methods.description: Check if the source of any imported resource changed.

methods.name: update_file
methods.description: Update a file information. Call this if an external program (not Godot) modified the file.

signals.name: filesystem_changed
signals.description: Emitted if the filesystem changed.

signals.name: sources_changed
signals.description: Emitted if the source of any imported file changed.

EditorFileSystemDirectory.name: EditorFileSystemDirectory
EditorFileSystemDirectory.brief_description: A diretory for the resource filesystem.

EditorPlugin.name: EditorPlugin
EditorPlugin.brief_description: Used by the editor to extend its functionality.
EditorPlugin.description: Plugins are used by the editor to extend functionality. The most common types of plugins are those which edit a given node or resource type, import plugins and export plugins.

methods.name: add_control_to_bottom_panel
methods.description: Add a control to the bottom panel (together with Output, Debug, Animation, etc). Returns a reference to the button added. It's up to you to hide/show the button when needed. If your plugin is being removed, also make sure to remove your control by calling [method remove_control_from_bottom_panel].

methods.name: add_control_to_container
methods.description:
Add a custom control to a container (see CONTAINER_* enum). There are many locations where custom controls can be added in the editor UI.
				Please remember that you have to manage the visibility of your custom controls yourself (and likely hide it after adding it).
				If your plugin is being removed, also make sure to remove your custom controls too.

methods.name: add_control_to_dock
methods.description:
Add the control to a specific dock slot (see DOCK_* enum for options).
				If the dock is repositioned and as long as the plugin is active, the editor will save the dock position on further sessions.
				If your plugin is being removed, also make sure to remove your control by calling [method remove_control_from_docks].

methods.name: add_custom_type
methods.description:
Add a custom type, which will appear in the list of nodes or resources. An icon can be optionally passed.
				When given node or resource is selected, the base type will be instanced (ie, "Spatial", "Control", "Resource"), then the script will be loaded and set to this object.
				You can use the [method EditorPlugin.handles] to check if your custom object is being edited by checking the script or using 'is' keyword.
				During run-time, this will be a simple object with a script so this function does not need to be called then.

methods.name: apply_changes
methods.description:
This method is called when the editor is about to save the project, switch to another tab, etc. It asks the plugin to apply any pending state changes to ensure consistency.
				This is used, for example, in shader editors to let the plugin know that it must apply the shader code being written by the user to the object.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear all the state and reset the object being edited to zero. This ensures your plugin does not keep editing a currently existing node, or a node from the wrong scene.

methods.name: create_spatial_gizmo
methods.description: This is used for plugins that create gizmos used by the spatial editor. Just check that the node passed in the "for_spatial" argument matches your plugin.

methods.name: edit
methods.description: This function is used for plugins that edit specific object types (nodes or resources). It requests the editor to edit the given object.

methods.name: forward_draw_over_canvas
methods.description: This function is called every time the 2D canvas editor draws (which overlays over the edited scene). Drawing over the supplied control will draw over the edited scene. To convert from control coordinates to edited scene coordinates (including zoom and offset), a transform is also provided. If you require this control to be redraw, call [method update_canvas].

methods.name: forward_spatial_gui_input
methods.description:
Implement this function if you are interested in 3D view screen input events. It will be called only if currently selected node is handled by your plugin.
				If you would like to always gets those input events then additionally use [method set_input_forwarding_always_enabled].

methods.name: get_base_control
methods.description: Get a base control where it's safe to place dialogs. Many plugins open dialogs and they need a control as a base to make sure they use the editor icons and theme.

methods.name: get_breakpoints
methods.description: This is for editors that edit script based objects. You can return a list of breakpoints in the format (script:line), for example: res://path_to_script.gd:25

methods.name: get_editor_settings
methods.description: Get the general settings for the editor (the same window that appears in the Settings menu).

methods.name: get_edited_scene_root
methods.description: Returns root node of currently edited scene.

methods.name: get_editor_viewport
methods.description: Get the main editor control. Use this as a parent for main screens.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Get the name of the editor plugin. For main scren plugins this is what will appear in the selector (which by default is 2D, 3D, Script).

methods.name: get_open_scenes
methods.description: Will return an Array of Strings which represent file paths to currently open scenes.

methods.name: get_resource_filesystem
methods.description: Get the filesystem cache for all resources in the project.

methods.name: get_resource_previewer
methods.description: Get tool for generating resource previews.

methods.name: get_script_editor
methods.description: Will return ScriptEditor object which contains informations about state of the scripts which are currently open by the editor.

methods.name: get_selection
methods.description: Get the object that handles the selection of nodes in the Scene Tree editor.

methods.name: get_state
methods.description: Get the state of your plugin editor. This is used when saving the scene (so state is kept when opening it again) and for switching tabs (so state can be restored when the tab returns).

methods.name: get_undo_redo
methods.description: Get the undo/redo object. Most actions in the editor can be undoable, so use this object to make sure this happens when it's worth it.

methods.name: get_window_layout
methods.description: Get the GUI layout of the plugin. This is used to save the project's editor layout when the [method EditorPlugin.queue_save_layout] is called or the editor layout was changed(For example changing the position of a dock).

methods.name: handles
methods.description: Implement this function if your plugin edits a specific type of object (Resource or Node). If you return true, then you will get the functions [method EditorPlugin.edit] and [method EditorPlugin.make_visible] called when the editor requests them.

methods.name: has_main_screen
methods.description: Return true if this is a main screen editor plugin (it goes in the main screen selector together with 2D, 3D, Script).

methods.name: inspect_object
methods.description: Inspect an object in the inspector.

methods.name: make_visible
methods.description:
This function will be called when the editor is requested to become visible. It is used for plugins that edit a specific object type.
				Remember that you have to manage the visibility of all your editor controls manually.

methods.name: open_scene_from_path
methods.description: Opens scene in editor. Do not use during plugin initialization. If you need, then use it together with [method Object.call_deferred].

methods.name: queue_save_layout
methods.description: Queue save the project's editor layout.

methods.name: reload_scene_from_path
methods.description: Reloads already loaded editor scene.

methods.name: remove_control_from_bottom_panel
methods.description: Remove the control from the bottom panel. Don't forget to call this if you added one, so the editor can remove it cleanly.

methods.name: remove_control_from_docks
methods.description: Remove the control from the dock. Don't forget to call this if you added one, so the editor can save the layout and remove it cleanly.

methods.name: remove_custom_type
methods.description: Remove a custom type added by [method EditorPlugin.add_custom_type]

methods.name: save_external_data
methods.description: This method is called after the editor saves the project or when it's closed. It asks the plugin to save edited external scenes/resources.

methods.name: set_input_event_forwarding_always_enabled
methods.description: Use this method if you always want to receive inputs from 3D view screen inside [method forward_spatial_gui_input]. It might be especially usable if your plugin will want to use raycast in the scene.

methods.name: set_state
methods.description: Restore the state saved by [method EditorPlugin.get_state].

methods.name: set_window_layout
methods.description: Restore the plugin GUI layout saved by [method EditorPlugin.get_window_layout].

methods.name: update_canvas
methods.description: Updates the control used to draw the edited scene over the 2D canvas. This is used together with [method forward_canvas_input_event].

signals.name: main_screen_changed
signals.description: Emitted when user change main screen view (2D, 3D, Script, AssetLib). Works also with screens which are defined by plugins.

signals.name: scene_changed
signals.description: Emitted when user change scene. The argument is a root node of freshly opened scene.

signals.name: scene_closed
signals.description: Emitted when user close scene. The argument is file path to a closed scene.

EditorResourcePreview.name: EditorResourcePreview
EditorResourcePreview.brief_description: Helper to generate previews of reources or files.
EditorResourcePreview.description: This object is used to generate previews for resources of files.

methods.name: add_preview_generator
methods.description: Create an own, custom preview generator.

methods.name: check_for_invalidation
methods.description: Check if the resource changed, if so it will be invalidated and the corresponding signal emitted.

methods.name: queue_edited_resource_preview
methods.description: Queue a resource being edited for preview (using an instance). Once the preview is ready, your receiver.receiver_func will be called either containing the preview texture or an empty texure (if no preview was possible). Callback must have the format: (path,texture,userdata). Userdata can be anything.

methods.name: queue_resource_preview
methods.description: Queue a resource file for preview (using a path). Once the preview is ready, your receiver.receiver_func will be called either containing the preview texture or an empty texure (if no preview was possible). Callback must have the format: (path,texture,userdata). Userdata can be anything.

methods.name: remove_preview_generator
methods.description: Remove a custom preview generator.

signals.name: preview_invalidated
signals.description: If a preview was invalidated (changed) this signal will emit (using the path of the preview)

EditorResourcePreviewGenerator.name: EditorResourcePreviewGenerator
EditorResourcePreviewGenerator.description: Custom code to generate previews. Please check "file_dialog/thumbnail_size" in EditorSettings to find out the right size to do previews at.

methods.name: generate
methods.description:
Generate a preview from a given resource. This must be always implemented.
			Returning an empty texture is an OK way to fail and let another generator take care.
			Care must be taken because this function is always called from a thread (not the main thread).

methods.name: generate_from_path
methods.description:
Generate a preview directly from a path, implementing this is optional, as default code will load and call generate()
			Returning an empty texture is an OK way to fail and let another generator take care.
			Care must be taken because this function is always called from a thread (not the main thread).

methods.name: handles
methods.description: Return if your generator supports this resource type.

EditorScript.name: EditorScript
EditorScript.brief_description: Simple script to perform changes in the currently edited scene.
EditorScript.description: This script can be run from the Scene -> Run Script menu option.

EditorSelection.name: EditorSelection
EditorSelection.brief_description: Manages the SceneTree selection in the editor.
EditorSelection.description: This object manages the SceneTree selection in the editor.

methods.name: add_node
methods.description: Add a node to the selection.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the selection.

methods.name: get_selected_nodes
methods.description: Get the list of selectes nodes.

methods.name: get_transformable_selected_nodes
methods.description: Get the list of selected nodes, optimized for transform operations (ie, moving them, rotating, etc). This list avoids situations where a node is selected and also chid/grandchild.

methods.name: remove_node
methods.description: Remove a node from the selection.

signals.name: selection_changed
signals.description: Emitted when the selection changes.

EditorSettings.name: EditorSettings
EditorSettings.brief_description: Object that holds the project-independent editor settings.
EditorSettings.description:
Object that holds the project-independent editor settings. These settings are generally visible in the Editor Settings menu.
		Accessing the settings is done by using the regular [Object] API, such as:
		[codeblock]
		settings.set(prop,value)
		settings.get(prop)
		list_of_settings = settings.get_property_list()
		[/codeblock]

methods.name: add_property_info
methods.description:
Add a custom property info to a property. The dictionary must contain: name:[String](the name of the property) and type:[int](see TYPE_* in [@Global Scope]), and optionally hint:[int](see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@Global Scope]), hint_string:[String].
				Example:
				[codeblock]
				editor_settings.set("category/property_name", 0)

				var property_info = {
				    "name": "category/property_name",
				    "type": TYPE_INT,
				    "hint": PROPERTY_HINT_ENUM,
				    "hint_string": "one,two,three"
				}

				editor_settings.add_property_info(property_info)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: erase
methods.description: Erase a given setting (pass full property path).

methods.name: get_favorite_dirs
methods.description: Get the list of favorite directories for this project.

methods.name: get_project_settings_path
methods.description: Get the specific project settings path. Projects all have an unique sub-directory inside the settings path where project specific settings are saved.

methods.name: get_recent_dirs
methods.description: Get the list of recently visited folders in the file dialog for this project.

methods.name: get_settings_path
methods.description:
Get the global settings path for the engine. Inside this path you can find some standard paths such as:
				settings/tmp - used for temporary storage of files
				settings/templates - where export templates are located

methods.name: set_favorite_dirs
methods.description: Set the list of favorite directories for this project.

methods.name: set_recent_dirs
methods.description: Set the list of recently visited folders in the file dialog for this project.

EditorSpatialGizmo.name: EditorSpatialGizmo
EditorSpatialGizmo.brief_description: Custom gizmo for editing Spatial objects.
EditorSpatialGizmo.description: Custom gizmo that is used for providing custom visualization and editing (handles) for 3D Spatial objects. These are created by [method EditorPlugin.create_spatial_gizmo].

methods.name: add_collision_triangles
methods.description: Add collision triangles to the gizmo for picking. A [TriangleMesh] can be generated from a regular [Mesh] too. Call this function during [method redraw].

methods.name: add_handles
methods.description:
Add a list of handles (points) which can be used to deform the object being edited.
				There are virtual functions which will be called upon editing of these handles. Call this function during [method redraw].

methods.name: add_lines
methods.description: Add lines to the gizmo (as sets of 2 points), with a given material. The lines are used for visualizing the gizmo. Call this function during [method redraw].

methods.name: add_mesh
methods.description: Add a mesh to the gizmo, this is used for visualization. Call this function during [method redraw].

methods.name: add_unscaled_billboard
methods.description: Add an unscaled billboard for visualization. Call this function during [method redraw].

methods.name: commit_handle
methods.description:
Commit a handle being edited (handles must have been prevously added by [method add_handles]).
				If the cancel parameter is true, an option to restore the edited value to the original is provided.

methods.name: get_handle_name
methods.description:
Get the name of an edited handle (handles must have been previously added by [method add_handles]).
				Handles can be named for reference to the user when editing.

methods.name: get_handle_value
methods.description: Get actual value of a handle. This value can be anything and used for eventually undoing the motion when calling [method commit_handle]

methods.name: redraw
methods.description: This function is called when the Spatial this gizmo refers to changes (the [method Spatial.update_gizmo] is called).

methods.name: set_handle
methods.description:
This function is used when the user drags a gizmo handle (previously added with [method add_handles]) in screen coordinates.
				The [Camera] is also provided so screen coordinates can be converted to raycasts.

methods.name: set_spatial_node
methods.description: Call this function once and upon creation of the gizmo, otherwise no other function will work. The argument is the node being edited by the gizmo.

methods.name: get_custom_level
methods.description: Returns the value of the commandline argument "-level".

methods.name: get_frames_drawn
methods.description: Return the total amount of frames drawn.

methods.name: get_frames_per_second
methods.description: Returns the frames per second of the running game.

methods.name: get_iterations_per_second
methods.description: Return the amount of fixed iterations per second (for fixed process and physics).

methods.name: get_main_loop
methods.description: Return the main loop object (see [MainLoop] and [SceneTree]).

methods.name: get_version_info
methods.description:
Returns the current engine version information in a Dictionary.

				"major"    - Holds the major version number as a String
				"minor"    - Holds the minor version number as a String
				"patch"    - Holds the patch version number as a String
				"status"   - Holds the status (e.g. "beta", "rc1", "rc2", ... "stable") as a String
				"revision" - Holds the revision (e.g. "custom-build") as a String
				"string"   - major + minor + patch + status + revision in a single String

methods.name: set_iterations_per_second
methods.description: Set the amount of fixed iterations per second (for fixed process and physics).

File.name: File
File.brief_description: Type to handle file reading and writing operations.

methods.name: close
methods.description: Close the currently opened file.

methods.name: eof_reached
methods.description: Return whether the file cursor reached the end of the file.

methods.name: file_exists
methods.description: Get whether or not the file in the specified path exists.

methods.name: get_16
methods.description: Get the next 16 bits from the file as an integer.

methods.name: get_32
methods.description: Get the next 32 bits from the file as an integer.

methods.name: get_64
methods.description: Get the next 64 bits from the file as an integer.

methods.name: get_8
methods.description: Get the next 8 bits from the file as an integer.

methods.name: get_as_text
methods.description: Get the whole file as a [String].

methods.name: get_buffer
methods.description: Get next len bytes of the file as a [PoolByteArray].

methods.name: get_csv_line
methods.description: Get the next value of the file in CSV (Comma Separated Values) format. You can pass a different delimiter to use other than the default "," (comma).

methods.name: get_double
methods.description: Get the next 64 bits from the file as a floating point number.

methods.name: get_endian_swap
methods.description: Get whether endian swap is enabled for this file.

methods.name: get_error
methods.description: Get the last error that happened when trying to perform operations. Compare with the [code]ERR_FILE_*[/code] constants from [@Global Scope].

methods.name: get_float
methods.description: Get the next 32 bits from the file as a floating point number.

methods.name: get_len
methods.description: Return the size of the file in bytes.

methods.name: get_line
methods.description: Get the next line of the file as a [String].

methods.name: get_md5
methods.description: Return a md5 String representing the file at the given path or an empty [String] on failure.

methods.name: get_pascal_string
methods.description: Get a [String] saved in Pascal format from the file.

methods.name: get_pos
methods.description: Return the file cursor position.

methods.name: get_real
methods.description: Get the next bits from the file as a floating point number.

methods.name: get_sha256
methods.description: Return a sha256 String representing the file at the given path or an empty [String] on failure.

methods.name: get_var
methods.description: Get the next Variant value from the file.

methods.name: is_open
methods.description: Return whether the file is currently opened.

methods.name: open
methods.description: Open the file for writing or reading, depending on the flags.

methods.name: open_compressed
methods.description: Open a compressed file for reading or writing. The compression_mode can be set as one of the COMPRESSION_* constants.

methods.name: open_encrypted
methods.description: Open an encrypted file in write or read mode. You need to pass a binary key to encrypt/decrypt it.

methods.name: open_encrypted_with_pass
methods.description: Open an encrypted file in write or read mode. You need to pass a password to encrypt/decrypt it.

methods.name: seek
methods.description: Change the file reading/writing cursor to the specified position (in bytes from the beginning of the file).

methods.name: seek_end
methods.description: Change the file reading/writing cursor to the specified position (in bytes from the end of the file). Note that this is an offset, so you should use negative numbers or the cursor will be at the end of the file.

methods.name: set_endian_swap
methods.description:
Set whether to swap the endianness of the file. Enable this if you're dealing with files written in big endian machines.
				Note that this is about the file format, not CPU type. This is always reseted to [code]false[/code] whenever you open the file.

methods.name: store_16
methods.description: Store an integer as 16 bits in the file.

methods.name: store_32
methods.description: Store an integer as 32 bits in the file.

methods.name: store_64
methods.description: Store an integer as 64 bits in the file.

methods.name: store_8
methods.description: Store an integer as 8 bits in the file.

methods.name: store_buffer
methods.description: Store the given array of bytes in the file.

methods.name: store_double
methods.description: Store a floating point number as 64 bits in the file.

methods.name: store_float
methods.description: Store a floating point number as 32 bits in the file.

methods.name: store_line
methods.description: Store the given [String] as a line in the file.

methods.name: store_pascal_string
methods.description: Store the given [String] as a line in the file in Pascal format (i.e. also store the length of the string).

methods.name: store_real
methods.description: Store a floating point number in the file.

methods.name: store_string
methods.description: Store the given [String] in the file.

methods.name: store_var
methods.description: Store any Variant value in the file.

constants.name: WRITE
constants.description: Open the file for writing. Create it if the file not exists and truncate if it exists.

constants.name: READ_WRITE
constants.description: Open the file for reading and writing, without truncating the file.

constants.name: WRITE_READ
constants.description: Open the file for reading and writing. Create it if the file not exists and truncate if it exists.

FileDialog.name: FileDialog
FileDialog.brief_description: Dialog for selecting files or directories in the filesystem.
FileDialog.description: FileDialog is a preset dialog used to choose files and directories in the filesystem. It supports filter masks.

methods.name: add_filter
methods.description: Add a custom filter. Filter format is: "mask ; description", example (C++): dialog->add_filter("*.png ; PNG Images");

methods.name: clear_filters
methods.description: Clear all the added filters in the dialog.

methods.name: get_access
methods.description: Return the file access permission of the dialog.

methods.name: get_current_dir
methods.description: Get the current working directory of the file dialog.

methods.name: get_current_file
methods.description: Get the current selected file of the file dialog (empty if none).

methods.name: get_current_path
methods.description: Get the current selected path (directory and file) of the file dialog (empty if none).

methods.name: get_mode
methods.description: Get the file dialog mode from the MODE_* enum.

methods.name: get_vbox
methods.description: Return the vertical box container of the dialog, custom controls can be added to it.

methods.name: invalidate
methods.description: Invalidate and update the current dialog content list.

methods.name: is_showing_hidden_files
methods.description: Return true if the diaog allows show hidden files.

methods.name: set_access
methods.description: Set the file access permission of the dialog(Must be one of [ACCESS_RESOURCES], [ACCESS_USERDATA] or [ACCESS_FILESYSTEM]).

methods.name: set_current_dir
methods.description: Set the current working directory of the file dialog.

methods.name: set_current_file
methods.description: Set the current selected file name of the file dialog.

methods.name: set_current_path
methods.description: Set the current selected file path of the file dialog.

methods.name: set_mode
methods.description: Set the file dialog mode from the MODE_* enum.

methods.name: set_show_hidden_files
methods.description: Set the dialog should show hidden files.

signals.name: dir_selected
signals.description: Event emitted when the user selects a directory.

signals.name: file_selected
signals.description: Event emitted when the user selects a file (double clicks it or presses the OK button).

signals.name: files_selected
signals.description: Event emitted when the user selects multiple files.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_FILE
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of one, and only one file.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_FILES
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of multiple files.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_DIR
constants.description: The dialog functions as a folder selector, disallowing the selection of any file.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_ANY
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of a file or a directory.

constants.name: MODE_SAVE_FILE
constants.description: The dialog will warn when a file exists.

constants.name: ACCESS_RESOURCES
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of file and directory.

constants.name: ACCESS_USERDATA
constants.description: The dialog allows ascess files under [Resource] path(res://) .

constants.name: ACCESS_FILESYSTEM
constants.description: The dialog allows ascess files in whole file system.

Font.name: Font
Font.brief_description: Internationalized font and text drawing support.
Font.description: Font contains an unicode compatible character set, as well as the ability to draw it with variable width, ascent, descent and kerning. For creating fonts from TTF files (or other font formats), see the editor support for fonts. TODO check wikipedia for graph of ascent/baseline/descent/height/etc.

methods.name: draw
methods.description: Draw "string" into a canvas item using the font at a given "pos" position, with "modulate" color, and optionally clipping the width. "pos" specifies the baseline, not the top. To draw from the top, [i]ascent[/i] must be added to the Y axis.

methods.name: draw_char
methods.description: Draw character "char" into a canvas item using the font at a given "pos" position, with "modulate" color, and optionally kerning if "next" is passed. clipping the width. "pos" specifies the baseline, not the top. To draw from the top, [i]ascent[/i] must be added to the Y axis. The width used by the character is returned, making this function useful for drawing strings character by character.

methods.name: get_ascent
methods.description: Return the font ascent (number of pixels above the baseline).

methods.name: get_descent
methods.description: Return the font descent (number of pixels below the baseline).

methods.name: get_height
methods.description: Return the total font height (ascent plus descent) in pixels.

methods.name: get_string_size
methods.description: Return the size of a string, taking kerning and advance into account.

methods.name: update_changes
methods.description: After editing a font (changing size, ascent, char rects, etc.). Call this function to propagate changes to controls that might use it.

FuncRef.name: FuncRef
FuncRef.brief_description: Reference to a function in an object.
FuncRef.description:
In GDScript, functions are not [i]first-class objects[/i]. This means it is impossible to store them directly as variables, return them from another function, or pass them as arguments.
		However, by creating a [FuncRef] using the [method @GDScript.funcref] function, a reference to a function in a given object can be created, passed around and called.

methods.name: set_function
methods.description: Set the name of the function to call on the object, without parentheses or any parameters.

methods.name: set_instance
methods.description: Set the object on which to call the referenced function. This object must be of a type actually inheriting from [Object], not a built-in type such as [int], [Vector2] or [Dictionary].

GDFunctionState.name: GDFunctionState
GDFunctionState.brief_description: State of a function call after yielding.
GDFunctionState.description: Calling [method @GDScript.yield] within a function will cause that function to yield and return its current state as an object of this type. The yielded function call can then be resumed later by calling [method resume] on this state object.

methods.name: is_valid
methods.description:
Check whether the function call may be resumed. This is not the case if the function state was already resumed.
				If [code]extended_check[/code] is enabled, it also checks if the associated script and object still exist. The extended check is done in debug mode as part of [method GDFunctionState.resume], but you can use this if you know you may be trying to resume without knowing for sure the object and/or script have survived up to that point.

methods.name: resume
methods.description:
Resume execution of the yielded function call.
				If handed an argument, return the argument from the [method @GDScript.yield] call in the yielded function call. You can pass e.g. an [Array] to hand multiple arguments.
				This function returns what the resumed function call returns, possibly another function state if yielded again.

GeometryInstance.name: GeometryInstance
GeometryInstance.brief_description: Base node for geometry based visual instances.
GeometryInstance.description: Base node for geometry based visual instances. Shares some common functionality like visibility and custom materials.

methods.name: get_material_override
methods.description: Return the material override for the whole geometry.

methods.name: set_material_override
methods.description: Set the material override for the whole geometry.

ProjectSettings.name: ProjectSettings
ProjectSettings.brief_description: Contains global variables accessible from everywhere.
ProjectSettings.description: Contains global variables accessible from everywhere. Use the normal [Object] API, such as "ProjectSettings.get(variable)", "ProjectSettings.set(variable,value)" or "ProjectSettings.has(variable)" to access them. Variables stored in project.godot are also loaded into ProjectSettings, making this object very useful for reading custom game configuration options.

methods.name: add_property_info
methods.description:
Add a custom property info to a property. The dictionary must contain: name:[String](the name of the property) and type:[int](see TYPE_* in [@Global Scope]), and optionally hint:[int](see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@Global Scope]), hint_string:[String].
				Example:
				[codeblock]
				ProjectSettings.set("category/property_name", 0)

				var property_info = {
				    "name": "category/property_name",
				    "type": TYPE_INT,
				    "hint": PROPERTY_HINT_ENUM,
				    "hint_string": "one,two,three"
				}

				ProjectSettings.add_property_info(property_info)
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the whole configuration (not recommended, may break things).

methods.name: get_order
methods.description: Return the order of a configuration value (influences when saved to the config file).

methods.name: globalize_path
methods.description: Convert a localized path (res://) to a full native OS path.

methods.name: has
methods.description: Return true if a configuration value is present.

methods.name: localize_path
methods.description: Convert a path to a localized path (res:// path).

methods.name: set_order
methods.description: Set the order of a configuration value (influences when saved to the config file).

Gradient.name: Gradient
Gradient.description: Given a set of colors, this node will interpolate them in order, meaning, that if you have color 1, color 2 and color3, the ramp will interpolate (generate the colors between two colors) from color 1 to color 2 and from color 2 to color 3. Initially the ramp will have 2 colors (black and white), one (black) at ramp lower offset offset 0 and the other (white) at the ramp higher offset 1.

methods.name: add_point
methods.description: Adds the specified color to the end of the ramp, with the specified offset

methods.name: get_color
methods.description: Returns the color of the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: get_colors
methods.description: Returns the colors in the ramp

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Returns the offset of the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: get_offsets
methods.description: Returns the offsets for the colors in this ramp

methods.name: get_point_count
methods.description: Returns the number of colors in the ramp

methods.name: interpolate
methods.description: Returns the interpolated color specified by [i]offset[/i]

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Removes the color at the index [i]offset[/i]

methods.name: set_color
methods.description: Sets the color of the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: set_colors
methods.description: Sets the colors for the specified amount of elements. Calling this function with a different number of elements than previously defined causes the ramp to resize its colors and offsets array to accommodate the new elements.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Sets the offset for the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: set_offsets
methods.description: Sets the offset for the specified amount of elements. Calling this function with a different number of elements than previously defined causes the ramp to resize its colors and offsets array to accommodate the new elements, all new colors will be black by default.

GraphEdit.name: GraphEdit
GraphEdit.brief_description: GraphEdit is an area capable of showing various GraphNodes. It manages connection events between them.
GraphEdit.description:
GraphEdit manages the showing of GraphNodes it contains, as well as connections an disconnections between them. Signals are sent for each of these two events. Disconnection between GraphNodes slots is disabled by default.
		It is greatly advised to enable low processor usage mode (see [method OS.set_low_processor_usage_mode]) when using GraphEdits.

methods.name: connect_node
methods.description: Create a connection between 'from_port' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_port' slot of 'to' GraphNode. If the connection already exists, no connection is created.

methods.name: disconnect_node
methods.description: Remove the connection between 'from_port' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_port' slot of 'to' GraphNode, if connection exists.

methods.name: get_connection_list
methods.description: Return an Array containing the list of connections. A connection consists in a structure of the form {from_slot: 0, from: "GraphNode name 0", to_slot: 1, to: "GraphNode name 1" }

methods.name: get_scroll_ofs
methods.description: Return the scroll offset.

methods.name: get_zoom
methods.description: Return the current zoom value.

methods.name: is_node_connected
methods.description: Return true if the 'from_port' slot of 'from' GraphNode is connected to the 'to_port' slot of 'to' GraphNode.

methods.name: is_right_disconnects_enabled
methods.description: Return true is the disconnection of connections is enable in the visual GraphEdit. False otherwise.

methods.name: set_right_disconnects
methods.description: Enable the disconnection of existing connections in the visual GraphEdit by left-clicking a connection and releasing into the void.

methods.name: set_zoom
methods.description: Set the zoom value of the GraphEdit. Zoom value is between [0.01; 1.728].

signals.name: _begin_node_move
signals.description: Signal sent at the beginning of a GraphNode movement.

signals.name: _end_node_move
signals.description: Signal sent at the end of a GraphNode movement.

signals.name: connection_request
signals.description: Signal sent to the GraphEdit when the connection between 'from_slot' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_slot' slot of 'to' GraphNode is attempted to be created.

signals.name: delete_nodes_request
signals.description: Signal sent when a GraphNode is attempted to be removed from the GraphEdit.

signals.name: disconnection_request
signals.description: Signal sent to the GraphEdit when the connection between 'from_slot' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_slot' slot of 'to' GraphNode is attempted to be removed.

signals.name: duplicate_nodes_request
signals.description: Signal sent when a GraphNode is attempted to be duplicated in the GraphEdit.

signals.name: popup_request
signals.description: Signal sent when a popup is requested. Happens on right-clicking in the GraphEdit. 'p_position' is the position of the mouse pointer when the signal is sent.

GraphNode.name: GraphNode
GraphNode.brief_description: A GraphNode is a container with several input and output slots allowing connections between GraphNodes. Slots can have different, incompatible types.
GraphNode.description: A GraphNode is a container defined by a title. It can have 1 or more input and output slots, which can be enabled (shown) or disabled (not shown) and have different (incompatible) types. Colors can also be assigned to slots. A tuple of input and output slots is defined for each GUI element included in the GraphNode. Input and output connections are left and right slots, but only enabled slots are counted as connections.

methods.name: clear_all_slots
methods.description: Disable all input and output slots of the GraphNode.

methods.name: clear_slot
methods.description: Disable input and output slot whose index is 'idx'.

methods.name: get_connection_input_color
methods.description: Return the color of the input connection 'idx'.

methods.name: get_connection_input_count
methods.description: Return the number of enabled input slots (connections) to the GraphNode.

methods.name: get_connection_input_pos
methods.description: Return the position of the input connection 'idx'.

methods.name: get_connection_input_type
methods.description: Return the type of the input connection 'idx'.

methods.name: get_connection_output_color
methods.description: Return the color of the output connection 'idx'.

methods.name: get_connection_output_count
methods.description: Return the number of enabled output slots (connections) of the GraphNode.

methods.name: get_connection_output_pos
methods.description: Return the position of the output connection 'idx'.

methods.name: get_connection_output_type
methods.description: Return the type of the output connection 'idx'.

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Return the offset of the GraphNode.

methods.name: get_slot_color_left
methods.description: Return the color set to 'idx' left (input) slot.

methods.name: get_slot_color_right
methods.description: Return the color set to 'idx' right (output) slot.

methods.name: get_slot_type_left
methods.description: Return the (integer) type of left (input) 'idx' slot.

methods.name: get_slot_type_right
methods.description: Return the (integer) type of right (output) 'idx' slot.

methods.name: get_title
methods.description: Return the title of the GraphNode.

methods.name: is_close_button_visible
methods.description: Returns true if the close button is shown. False otherwise.

methods.name: is_slot_enabled_left
methods.description: Return true if left (input) slot 'idx' is enabled. False otherwise.

methods.name: is_slot_enabled_right
methods.description: Return true if right (output) slot 'idx' is enabled. False otherwise.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Set the offset of the GraphNode.

methods.name: set_show_close_button
methods.description: Show the close button on the GraphNode if 'show' is true (disabled by default). If enabled, a connection on the signal close_request is needed for the close button to work.

methods.name: set_title
methods.description: Set the title of the GraphNode.

signals.name: close_request
signals.description: Signal sent on closing the GraphNode.

signals.name: dragged
signals.description: Signal sent when the GraphNode is dragged.

signals.name: offset_changed
signals.description: Signal sent when the GraphNode is moved.

signals.name: raise_request
signals.description: Signal sent when the GraphNode is requested to be displayed over other ones. Happens on focusing (clicking into) the GraphNode.

GridContainer.name: GridContainer
GridContainer.brief_description: Grid container used to arrange elements in a grid like layout
GridContainer.description: Grid container will arrange its children in a grid like structure, the grid columns are specified using the [method set_columns] method and the number of rows will be equal to the number of children in the container divided by the number of columns, for example: if the container has 5 children, and 2 columns, there will be 3 rows in the container. Notice that grid layout will preserve the columns and rows for every size of the container.

methods.name: get_columns
methods.description: Returns the number of columns in this container

methods.name: set_columns
methods.description: Sets the numbers of columns in the container, then reorder its children to accommodate the new layout

GrooveJoint2D.name: GrooveJoint2D
GrooveJoint2D.description: Groove constraint for 2D physics. This is useful for making a body "slide" through a segment placed in another.

methods.name: get_initial_offset
methods.description: Set the final offset of the groove on body A.

methods.name: get_length
methods.description: Return the length of the groove.

methods.name: set_initial_offset
methods.description: Set the initial offset of the groove on body A.

methods.name: set_length
methods.description: Set the length of the groove.

HScrollBar.name: HScrollBar
HScrollBar.description: Horizontal scroll bar. See [ScrollBar]. This one goes from left (min) to right (max).

HSeparator.name: HSeparator
HSeparator.description: Horizontal separator. See [Separator]. It is used to separate objects vertically, though (but it looks horizontal!).

HSlider.name: HSlider
HSlider.description: Horizontal slider. See [Slider]. This one goes from left (min) to right (max).

HSplitContainer.name: HSplitContainer
HSplitContainer.description: Horizontal split container. See [SplitContainer]. This goes from left to right.

HTTPClient.name: HTTPClient
HTTPClient.description:
Hyper-text transfer protocol client. Supports SSL and SSL server certificate verification.
		Can be reused to connect to different hosts and make many requests.

methods.name: close
methods.description: Cloces the current connection, allows for reusal of [HTTPClient].

methods.name: connect_to_host
methods.description:
Connect to a host. This needs to be done before any requests are sent.
				The host should not have http:// prepended but will strip the protocol identifier if provided.
				verify_host will check the SSL identity of the host if set to true.

methods.name: get_connection
methods.description: Return current connection.

methods.name: get_response_body_length
methods.description: Return the response's body length.

methods.name: get_response_code
methods.description: Return the HTTP status code of the response.

methods.name: get_response_headers
methods.description: Return the response headers.

methods.name: get_response_headers_as_dictionary
methods.description:
Returns all response headers as dictionary where the case-sensitivity of the keys and values is kept like the server delivers it. A value is a simple String, this string can have more than one value where "; " is used as separator.
				Structure: ("key":"value1; value2")
				Example: (content-length:12), (Content-Type:application/json; charset=UTF-8)

methods.name: get_status
methods.description: Returns a STATUS_* enum constant. Need to call [method poll] in order to get status updates.

methods.name: has_response
methods.description: Return whether this [HTTPClient] has a response available.

methods.name: is_blocking_mode_enabled
methods.description: Return whether blocking mode is enabled.

methods.name: is_response_chunked
methods.description: Return whether this [HTTPClient] has a response that is chunked.

methods.name: poll
methods.description: This needs to be called in order to have any request processed. Check results with [method get_status]

methods.name: query_string_from_dict
methods.description:
Generates a GET/POST application/x-www-form-urlencoded style query string from a provided dictionary, e.g.:
				[codeblock]
				var fields = {"username": "user", "password": "pass"}
				String queryString = httpClient.query_string_from_dict(fields)
				returns:= "username=user&password=pass"
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: read_response_body_chunk
methods.description: Reads one chunk from the response.

methods.name: request
request_raw
methods.description:
Sends a raw request to the connected host. The url is what is normally behind the hostname, i.e. in [code]http://somehost.com/index.php[/code], url would be "index.php".
				Headers are HTTP request headers.
				Sends body raw, as a byte array, does not encode it in any way.

methods.name: send_body_data
methods.description: Stub function

methods.name: send_body_text
methods.description: Stub function

methods.name: set_blocking_mode
methods.description: If set to true, execution will block until all data is read from the response.

methods.name: set_connection
methods.description: Set connection to use, for this client.

methods.name: set_read_chunk_size
methods.description: Sets the size of the buffer used and maximum bytes to read per iteration. see [method read_response_body_chunk]

HTTPRequest.name: HTTPRequest
HTTPRequest.brief_description: A Node with the ability to send HTTP requests.
HTTPRequest.description:
A Node with the ability to send HTTP requests. Uses a [HTTPClient] internally, supports HTTPS.
		Can be used to make HTTP requests or download files via HTTP.

methods.name: cancel_request
methods.description: Cancel the current request.

methods.name: get_body_size
methods.description: Return the response body length.

methods.name: get_body_size_limit
methods.description: Return current body size limit.

methods.name: get_download_file
methods.description: Return the file this request will download into.

methods.name: get_downloaded_bytes

"src" [Image] and "mask" [Image] *must* have the same size (width and height) but they can have different formats

Input.name: Input

Input.description: A Singleton that deals with inputs. This includes key presses, mouse buttons and movement, joypads, and input actions.

methods.name: action_press

methods.name: get_connected_joypads
methods.description: Returns an [Array] containing the device IDs of all currently connected joypads.

methods.name: get_gyroscope
methods.description: If the device has a gyroscope, this will return the rate of rotation in rad/s around a device's x, y, and z axis.

methods.description: Returns the duration of the current vibration effect in seconds.

methods.description: Returns the strength of the joypad vibration: x is the strength of the weak motor, and y is the strength of the strong motor.

methods.description: Returns the mouse speed for the last time the cursor was moved, and this until the next frame where the mouse moves. This means that even if the mouse is not moving, this function will still return the value of the last motion.

methods.name: get_magnetometer
methods.description: If the device has a magnetometer, this will return the magnetic field strength in micro-Tesla for all axes.

methods.description: Returns mouse buttons as a bitmask. If multiple mouse buttons are pressed at the same time the bits are added together.

methods.name: get_mouse_mode
methods.description: Return the mouse mode. See the constants for more information.

methods.name: is_action_pressed
methods.description: Returns true or false depending on whether the action event is pressed. Actions and their events can be set in the Project Settings / Input Map tab. Or be set with [InputMap].

methods.name: is_joy_button_pressed
methods.description: Returns if the joypad button at the given index is currently pressed. (see JOY_* constants in [@Global Scope])

methods.name: is_joy_known
methods.description: Returns if the specified device is known by the system. This means that it sets all button and axis indices exactly as defined in the JOY_* constants (see [@Global Scope]). Unknown joypads are not expected to match these constants, but you can still retrieve events from them.

methods.name: is_key_pressed
methods.description: Returns true or false depending on whether the key is pressed or not. You can pass KEY_*, which are pre-defined constants listed in [@Global Scope].

methods.name: is_mouse_button_pressed
methods.description: Returns true or false depending on whether mouse button is pressed or not. You can pass BUTTON_*, which are pre-defined constants listed in [@Global Scope].

methods.name: remove_joy_mapping

methods.name: set_custom_mouse_cursor

methods.name: set_mouse_mode
methods.description: Set the mouse mode. See the constants for more information.

methods.name: start_joy_vibration
methods.description:
Starts to vibrate the joypad. Joypads usually come with two rumble motors, a strong and a weak one. weak_magnitude is the strength of the weak motor (between 0 and 1) and strong_magnitude is the strength of the strong motor (between 0 and 1). duration is the duration of the effect in seconds (a duration of 0 will try to play the vibration indefinitely).
				Note that not every hardware is compatible with long effect durations, it is recommended to restart an effect if in need to play it for more than a few seconds.

InstancePlaceholder.name: InstancePlaceholder
InstancePlaceholder.brief_description: Placeholder for the root [Node] of a [PackedScene].
InstancePlaceholder.description:
Turning on the option [b]Load As Placeholder[/b] for an instanced scene in the editor causes it to be replaced by an InstacePlaceholder when running the game. This makes it possible to delay actually loading the scene until calling [method replace_by_instance]. This is useful to avoid loading large scenes all at once by loading parts of it selectively.
		The InstancePlaceholder does not have a transform. This causes any child nodes to be positioned relatively to the Viewport from point (0,0), rather than their parent as displayed in the editor. Replacing the placeholder with a scene with a transform will transform children relatively to their parent again.

methods.name: get_instance_path
methods.description: Retrieve the path to the [PackedScene] resource file that is loaded by default when calling [method replace_by_instance].

methods.name: replace_by_instance
methods.description: Replace this placeholder by the scene handed as an argument, or the original scene if no argument is given. As for all resources, the scene is loaded only if it's not loaded already. By manually loading the scene beforehand, delays caused by this function can be avoided.

KinematicBody.name: KinematicBody
KinematicBody.description:
Kinematic bodies are special types of bodies that are meant to be user-controlled. They are not affected by physics at all (to other types of bodies, such a character or a rigid body, these are the same as a static body). They have however, two main uses:
		Simulated Motion: When these bodies are moved manually, either from code or from an AnimationPlayer (with process mode set to fixed), the physics will automatically compute an estimate of their linear and angular velocity. This makes them very useful for moving platforms or other AnimationPlayer-controlled objects (like a door, a bridge that opens, etc).
		Kinematic Characters: KinematicBody also has an api for moving objects (the [method move] method) while performing collision tests. This makes them really useful to implement characters that collide against a world, but that don't require advanced physics.

methods.name: move
methods.description:
Move the body in the given direction, stopping if there is an obstacle. If as a result of a movement there will be any collision then informations about this collision will be in returned dictionary. Dictionary will contains those keys:
				- "position" - collision position
				- "normal" - collision normal
				- "local_shape" - id of this kinematic body shape that took part in a collision
				- "travel" -  traveled movement before being stopped
				- "remainder" - remaining movement before being stopped
				- "collider_id" - id of the collider, it can be used when dealing with [PhysicsServer]
				- "collider" - colliding body
				- "collider_shape_index" - index of the colliding shape, inside collider body "collider_metadata"
				If the body did not intersect anything, then an empty dictionary (dir.empty()==true) is returned instead. Please note that this method is less user friendly than [method move_and_slide]. If you don't want to program each edge case manually, then it's recommended to use [method move_and_slide] instead.

KinematicBody2D.name: KinematicBody2D
KinematicBody2D.description:
Kinematic bodies are special types of bodies that are meant to be user-controlled. They are not affected by physics at all (to other types of bodies, such a character or a rigid body, these are the same as a static body). They have however, two main uses:
		Simulated Motion: When these bodies are moved manually, either from code or from an AnimationPlayer (with process mode set to fixed), the physics will automatically compute an estimate of their linear and angular velocity. This makes them very useful for moving platforms or other AnimationPlayer-controlled objects (like a door, a bridge that opens, etc).
		Kinematic Characters: KinematicBody2D also has an api for moving objects (the [method move] method) while performing collision tests. This makes them really useful to implement characters that collide against a world, but that don't require advanced physics.

methods.name: get_collision_collider_velocity
methods.description: Return the velocity of the body that collided with this one.

methods.name: move
methods.description:
Move the body in the given direction, stopping if there is an obstacle. If as a result of a movement there will be any collision then informations about this collision will be in returned dictionary.	Dictionary will contains those keys:
				- "position" - collision position
				- "normal" - collision normal
				- "local_shape" - id of this kinematic body shape that took part in a collision
				- "travel" -  traveled movement before being stopped
				- "remainder" - remaining movement before being stopped
				- "collider_id" - id of the collider, it can be used when dealing with [Physics2DServer]
				- "collider" - colliding body
				- "collider_shape_index" - index of the colliding shape, inside collider body "collider_metadata"
				If the body did not intersect anything, then an empty dictionary (dir.empty()==true) is returned instead. Please note that this method is less user friendly than [method move_and_slide]. If you don't want to program each edge case manually, then it's recommended to use [method move_and_slide] instead.

methods.name: test_move
methods.description: Return true if there would be a collision if the body moved from the given point in the given direction.

Label.name: Label
Label.description: Label is a control that displays formatted text, optionally autowrapping it to the [Control] area. It inherits from range to be able to scroll wrapped text vertically.

methods.name: get_align
methods.description: Return the alignment mode (any of the ALIGN_* enumeration values).

methods.name: get_line_count
methods.description: Return the amount of lines.

methods.name: get_line_height
methods.description: Return the height of a line.

methods.name: get_lines_skipped
methods.description: Return the the number of lines to skipped before displaying.

methods.name: get_max_lines_visible
methods.description: Return the restricted number of lines to display. Returns -1 if unrestricted.

methods.name: get_percent_visible
methods.description: Return the restricted number of characters to display (as a percentage of the total text).

methods.name: get_text
methods.description: Return the label text. Text can contain newlines.

methods.name: get_total_character_count
methods.description: Return the total length of the text.

methods.name: get_valign
methods.description: Return the vertical alignment mode (any of the VALIGN_* enumeration values).

methods.name: get_visible_characters
methods.description: Return the restricted number of characters to display. Returns -1 if unrestricted.

methods.name: has_autowrap
