methods.description: Return the state of the [i]autowrap[/i] mode (see [method set_autowrap]).

methods.name: is_clipping_text
methods.description: Return true if text would be cut off if it is too wide.

methods.name: is_uppercase
methods.description: Return true if text is displayed in all capitals.

methods.name: set_align
methods.description: Sets the alignment mode to any of the ALIGN_* enumeration values.

methods.name: set_autowrap
methods.description: Set [i]autowrap[/i] mode. When enabled, autowrap will fit text to the control width, breaking sentences when they exceed the available horizontal space. When disabled, the label minimum width becomes the width of the longest row, and the minimum height large enough to fit all rows.

methods.name: set_clip_text
methods.description: Cuts off the rest of the text if it is too wide.

methods.name: set_lines_skipped
methods.description: Sets the number of lines to skip before displaying. Useful for scrolling text.

methods.name: set_max_lines_visible
methods.description: Restricts the number of lines to display. Set to -1 to disable.

methods.name: set_percent_visible
methods.description: Restricts the number of characters to display (as a percentage of the total text).

methods.name: set_text
methods.description: Set the label text. Text can contain newlines.

methods.name: set_uppercase
methods.description: Display text in all capitals.

methods.name: set_valign
methods.description: Sets the vertical alignment mode to any of the VALIGN_* enumeration values.

methods.name: set_visible_characters
methods.description: Restricts the number of characters to display. Set to -1 to disable.

constants.name: ALIGN_FILL
constants.description: Expand row whitespaces to fit the width.

constants.name: VALIGN_TOP
constants.description: Align the whole text to the top.

constants.name: VALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Align the whole text to the center.

constants.name: VALIGN_BOTTOM
constants.description: Align the whole text to the bottom.

constants.name: VALIGN_FILL
constants.description: Align the whole text by spreading the rows.

LargeTexture.name: LargeTexture
LargeTexture.brief_description: A Texture capable of storing many smaller Textures with offsets.
LargeTexture.description:
A Texture capable of storing many smaller Textures with offsets.
		You can dynamically add pieces(Textures) to this fLargeTexture] using different offsets.

methods.name: add_piece
methods.description: Add another [Texture] to this [LargeTexture], starting on offset "ofs".

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the [LargeTexture].

methods.name: get_piece_count
methods.description: Return the number of pieces currently in this [LargeTexture].

methods.name: get_piece_offset
methods.description: Return the offset of the piece with index "idx".

methods.name: get_piece_texture
methods.description: Return the [Texture] of the piece with index "idx".

methods.name: set_piece_offset
methods.description: Set the offset of the piece with index "idx" to "ofs".

methods.name: set_piece_texture
methods.description: Set the [Texture] of the piece with index "idx" to  "ofs".

methods.name: set_size
methods.description: Set the size of this [LargeTexture].

Light.name: Light
Light.brief_description: Provides a base class for different kinds of light nodes.
Light.description: Light is the abstract base class for light nodes, so it shouldn't be used directly (It can't be instanced). Other types of light nodes inherit from it. Light contains the common variables and parameters used for lighting.

Light2D.name: Light2D
Light2D.brief_description: Node that casts light in a 2D environment.
Light2D.description: Node that casts light in a 2D environment. Light is defined by a (usually grayscale) texture, a color, an energy value, a mode (see constants), and various other parameters (range and shadows-related). Note that Light2D can be used as a mask.

methods.name: get_color
methods.description: Return the color of the Light2D.

methods.name: get_energy
methods.description: Return the energy value of the Light2D.

methods.name: get_height
methods.description: Return the height of the Light2D. Used with 2D normalmapping.

methods.name: get_layer_range_max
methods.description: Set the maximum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: get_layer_range_min
methods.description: Get the minimum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: get_mode
methods.description: Return the current mode set to the Light2D.

methods.name: get_shadow_buffer_size
methods.description: Return the shadow buffer size.

methods.name: get_shadow_color
methods.description: Return the color of casted shadows for this Light2D.

methods.name: get_texture
methods.description: Return the texture of the Light2D.

methods.name: get_texture_offset
methods.description: Return the offset of the light texture.

methods.name: get_texture_scale
methods.description: Return the scale value of the light texture.

methods.name: get_z_range_max
methods.description: Get the maximum Z value that objects of the scene can be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: get_z_range_min
methods.description: Get the minimum Z value that objects of the scene have to be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: is_enabled
methods.description: Return true if the Light2D is enabled, false if it is not.

methods.name: is_shadow_enabled
methods.description: Return true if shadow casting is enabled for this Light2D, else return false.

methods.name: set_color
methods.description: Set the color of the Light2D.

methods.name: set_enabled
methods.description: Switches the Light2D on or off, depending on the 'enabled' parameter.

methods.name: set_energy
methods.description: Set the energy value of the Light2D. The bigger the value, the stronger the light.

methods.name: set_height
methods.description: Set the height of the Light2D. Used with 2D normalmapping.

methods.name: set_item_cull_mask
methods.description: Set the item mask of the Light2D to 'item_mask' value.

methods.name: set_item_shadow_cull_mask
methods.description: Set the item shadow mask to 'item_shadow_mask' value.

methods.name: set_layer_range_max
methods.description: Set the maximum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: set_layer_range_min
methods.description: Set the minimum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: set_mode
methods.description: Set the behaviour mode of the Light2D. Use constants defined in the constants section.

methods.name: set_shadow_buffer_size
methods.description: Set the shadow buffer size.

methods.name: set_shadow_color
methods.description: Set the color of casted shadows for this Light2D.

methods.name: set_shadow_enabled
methods.description: Enable or disable shadows casting from this Light2D according to the 'enabled' parameter.

methods.name: set_texture
methods.description: Set the texture of the Light2D.

methods.name: set_texture_offset
methods.description: Set the offset of the light texture.

methods.name: set_texture_scale
methods.description: Set the scale value of the light texture.

methods.name: set_z_range_max
methods.description: Set the maximum Z value that objects of the scene can be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: set_z_range_min
methods.description: Set the minimum Z value that objects of the scene have to be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

constants.name: MODE_ADD
constants.description: Adds the value of pixels corresponding to the Light2D to the values of pixels under it. This is the common behaviour of a light.

constants.name: MODE_SUB
constants.description: Subtract the value of pixels corresponding to the Light2D to the values of pixels under it, resulting in inversed light effect.

constants.name: MODE_MIX
constants.description: Mix the value of pixels corresponding to the Light2D to the values of pixels under it by linear interpolation.

constants.name: MODE_MASK
constants.description: The light texture of the Light2D is used as a mask, hiding or revealing parts of the screen underneath depending on the value of each pixel of the light (mask) texture.

LightOccluder2D.name: LightOccluder2D
LightOccluder2D.brief_description: Occludes light cast by a Light2D, thus casting shadows.
LightOccluder2D.description: Occludes light cast by a Light2D, thus casting shadows. The LightOccluder2D must be provided with a shape (see OccluderPolygon2D) that allows the shadow to be computed. This shape affects the resulting shadow, while the shape of the representating asset shadowed does not actually affect shadows.

methods.name: get_occluder_light_mask
methods.description: Return the light mask of the LightOccluder2D.

methods.name: get_occluder_polygon
methods.description: Return the OccluderPolygon2D that defines the LightOccluder2D.

methods.name: set_occluder_light_mask
methods.description: Set the LightOccluder2D light mask. The LightOccluder2D will cast shadows only from Light2Ds that belong to the same light mask(s).

methods.name: set_occluder_polygon
methods.description: Set the OccluderPolygon2D that defines the LightOccluder2D.

LineEdit.name: LineEdit
LineEdit.brief_description: Control that provides single line string editing.
LineEdit.description: LineEdit provides a single line string editor, used for text fields.

methods.name: append_at_cursor
methods.description: Append text at cursor, scrolling the [LineEdit] when needed.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the [LineEdit] text.

methods.name: cursor_get_blink_enabled
methods.description: Gets whether the line edit caret is blinking.

methods.name: cursor_get_blink_speed
methods.description: Gets the line edit caret blink speed.

methods.name: cursor_set_blink_enabled
methods.description: Set the line edit caret to blink.

methods.name: cursor_set_blink_speed
methods.description: Set the line edit caret blink speed. Cannot be less then or equal to 0.

methods.name: get_cursor_pos
methods.description: Return the cursor position inside the [LineEdit].

methods.name: get_max_length
methods.description: Return the maximum amount of characters the [LineEdit] can edit. If 0 is returned, no limit exists.

methods.name: get_text
methods.description: Return the text in the [LineEdit].

methods.name: is_editable
methods.description: Return the [i]editable[/i] status of the [LineEdit] (see [method set_editable]).

methods.name: is_secret
methods.description: Return the [i]secret[/i] status of the [LineEdit] (see [method set_secret]).

methods.name: select_all
methods.description: Select the whole string.

methods.name: set_cursor_pos
methods.description: Set the cursor position inside the [LineEdit], causing it to scroll if needed.

methods.name: set_editable
methods.description: Set the [i]editable[/i] status of the [LineEdit]. When disabled, existing text can't be modified and new text can't be added.

methods.name: set_max_length
methods.description: Set the maximum amount of characters the [LineEdit] can edit, and cropping existing text in case it exceeds that limit. Setting 0 removes the limit.

methods.name: set_secret
methods.description: Set the [i]secret[/i] status of the [LineEdit]. When enabled, every character is displayed as "*".

methods.name: set_text
methods.description: Set the text in the [LineEdit], clearing the existing one and the selection.

signals.name: text_changed
signals.description: When the text changes, this signal is emitted.

signals.name: text_entered
signals.description: This signal is emitted when the user presses KEY_ENTER on the [LineEdit]. This signal is often used as an alternate confirmation mechanism in dialogs.

LineShape2D.name: LineShape2D
LineShape2D.description: Line shape for 2D collision objects. It works like a 2D plane and will not allow any body to go to the negative side. Not recommended for rigid bodies, and usually not recommended for static bodies either because it forces checks against it on every frame.

methods.name: get_d
methods.description: Return the line distance from the origin.

methods.name: get_normal
methods.description: Return the line normal.

methods.name: set_d
methods.description: Set the line distance from the origin.

methods.name: set_normal
methods.description: Set the line normal.

LinkButton.name: LinkButton
LinkButton.brief_description: Simple button used to represent a link to some resource
LinkButton.description: This kind of buttons are primarily used when the interaction with the button causes a context change (like linking to a web page).

methods.name: get_text
methods.description: Returns the text of the button.

methods.name: get_underline_mode
methods.description: Returns the underline mode for this button.

methods.name: set_text
methods.description: Sets the text of the button.

methods.name: set_underline_mode
methods.description: Sets the underline mode for this button, the argument must be one of the [LinkButton] constants (see constants section).

constants.name: UNDERLINE_MODE_ALWAYS
constants.description: The LinkButton will always show an underline at the bottom of its text

constants.name: UNDERLINE_MODE_ON_HOVER
constants.description: The LinkButton will show an underline at the bottom of its text when the mouse cursor is over it.

constants.name: UNDERLINE_MODE_NEVER
constants.description: The LinkButton will never show an underline at the bottom of its text.

MainLoop.name: MainLoop
MainLoop.brief_description: Main loop is the abstract main loop base class.
MainLoop.description: Main loop is the abstract main loop base class. All other main loop classes are derived from it. Upon application start, a [MainLoop] has to be provided to OS, else the application will exit. This happens automatically (and a [SceneTree] is created), unless a main [Script] is supplied, which may or not create and return a [MainLoop].

MarginContainer.name: MarginContainer
MarginContainer.description: Simple margin container. Adds a left margin to anything contained.

Material.name: Material
Material.brief_description: Abstract base [Resource] for coloring and shading geometry.
Material.description: Material is a base [Resource] used for coloring and shading geometry. All materials inherit from it and almost all [VisualInstance] derived nodes carry a Material. A few flags and parameters are shared between all material types and are configured here.

MenuButton.name: MenuButton
MenuButton.brief_description: Special button that brings up a [PopupMenu] when clicked.
MenuButton.description: Special button that brings up a [PopupMenu] when clicked. That's pretty much all it does, as it's just a helper class when building GUIs.

methods.name: get_popup
methods.description: Return the [PopupMenu] contained in this button.

Mesh.name: Mesh
Mesh.brief_description: A [Resource] that contains vertex-array based geometry.
Mesh.description: Mesh is a type of [Resource] that contains vertex-array based geometry, divided in [i]surfaces[/i]. Each surface contains a completely separate array and a material used to draw it. Design wise, a mesh with multiple surfaces is preferred to a single surface, because objects created in 3D editing software commonly contain multiple materials.

constants.name: PRIMITIVE_POINTS
constants.description: Render array as points (one vertex equals one point).

constants.name: PRIMITIVE_LINES
constants.description: Render array as lines (every two vertices a line is created).

constants.name: PRIMITIVE_LINE_LOOP
constants.description: Render array as line loop (like line strip, but closed).

constants.name: PRIMITIVE_TRIANGLES
constants.description: Render array as triangles (every three vertices a triangle is created).

MeshInstance.name: MeshInstance
MeshInstance.brief_description: Node that instances meshes into a scenario.
MeshInstance.description: MeshInstance is a [Node] that takes a [Mesh] resource and adds it to the current scenario by creating an instance of it. This is the class most often used to get 3D geometry rendered and can be used to instance a single [Mesh] in many places. This allows to reuse geometry and save on resources. When a [Mesh] has to be instanced more than thousands of times at close proximity, consider using a [MultiMesh] in a [MultiMeshInstance] instead.

methods.name: create_trimesh_collision
methods.description: This helper creates a [StaticBody] child [Node] using the mesh geometry as collision. It's mainly used for testing.

methods.name: get_mesh
methods.description: Return the current [Mesh] resource for the instance.

methods.name: set_mesh
methods.description: Set the [Mesh] resource for the instance.

MeshLibrary.name: MeshLibrary
MeshLibrary.description: Library of meshes. Contains a list of [Mesh] resources, each with name and ID. Useful for GridMap or painting Terrain.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the library.

methods.name: create_item
methods.description: Create a new item in the library, supplied an id.

methods.name: get_item_list
methods.description: Return the list of items.

methods.name: get_item_mesh
methods.description: Return the mesh of the item.

methods.name: get_item_name
methods.description: Return the name of the item.

methods.name: get_last_unused_item_id
methods.description: Get an unused id for a new item.

methods.name: remove_item
methods.description: Remove the item.

methods.name: set_item_mesh
methods.description: Set the mesh of the item.

methods.name: set_item_name
methods.description: Set the name of the item.

MultiMesh.name: MultiMesh
MultiMesh.description:
MultiMesh provides low level mesh instancing. If the amount of [Mesh] instances needed goes from hundreds to thousands (and most need to be visible at close proximity) creating such a large amount of [MeshInstance] nodes may affect performance by using too much CPU or video memory.
		For this case a MultiMesh becomes very useful, as it can draw thousands of instances with little API overhead.
		As a drawback, if the instances are too far away of each other, performance may be reduced as every single instance will always rendered (they are spatially indexed as one, for the whole object).
		Since instances may have any behavior, the Rect3 used for visibility must be provided by the user.

methods.name: get_aabb
methods.description: Return the visibility Rect3.

methods.name: get_instance_color
methods.description: Get the color of a specific instance.

methods.name: get_instance_count
methods.description: Return the amount of instances that is going to be drawn.

methods.name: get_instance_transform
methods.description: Return the transform of a specific instance.

methods.name: get_mesh
methods.description: Return the [Mesh] resource drawn as multiple instances.

methods.name: set_instance_color
methods.description: Set the color of a specific instance.

methods.name: set_instance_count
methods.description: Set the amount of instances that is going to be drawn. Changing this number will erase all the existing instance transform and color data.

methods.name: set_instance_transform
methods.description: Set the transform for a specific instance.

methods.name: set_mesh
methods.description: Set the [Mesh] resource to be drawn in multiple instances.

MultiMeshInstance.name: MultiMeshInstance
MultiMeshInstance.description: MultiMeshInstance is a [Node] that takes a [MultiMesh] resource and adds it to the current scenario by creating an instance of it (yes, this is an instance of instances).

methods.name: get_multimesh
methods.description: Return the [MultiMesh] that is used for instancing.

methods.name: set_multimesh
methods.description: Set the [MultiMesh] to be instance.

Mutex.name: Mutex
Mutex.description: A synchronization Mutex. Element used in multi-threadding. Basically a binary [Semaphore]. Guarantees that only one thread has this lock, can be used to protect a critical section.

methods.name: lock
methods.description: Lock this [Mutex], blocks until it is unlocked by the current owner.

methods.name: try_lock
methods.description: Try locking this [Mutex], does not block. Returns [OK] on success else [ERR_BUSY].

methods.name: unlock
methods.description: Unlock this [Mutex], leaving it to others threads.

NetworkedMultiplayerENet.name: NetworkedMultiplayerENet
NetworkedMultiplayerENet.brief_description: PacketPeer implementation using the ENet library.
NetworkedMultiplayerENet.description: A connection (or a listening server) that should be passed to [method SceneTree.set_network_peer]. Socket events can be handled by connecting to [SceneTree] signals.

Node.name: Node
Node.brief_description: Base class for all the [i]scene[/i] elements.
Node.description:
Nodes are the base bricks with which Godot games are developed. They can be set as children of other nodes, resulting in a tree arrangement. A given node can contain any number of nodes as children (but there is only one scene tree root node) with the requirement that all siblings (direct children of a node) should have unique names.
		Any tree of nodes is called a [i]scene[/i]. Scenes can be saved to the disk and then instanced into other scenes. This allows for very high flexibility in the architecture and data model of the projects. Nodes can optionally be added to groups. This makes it easy to reach a number of nodes from the code (for example an "enemies" group) to perform grouped actions.
		[b]Scene tree:[/b] The [SceneTree] contains the active tree of nodes. When a node is added to the scene tree, it receives the NOTIFICATION_ENTER_TREE notification and its [method _enter_tree] callback is triggered. Children nodes are always added [i]after[/i] their parent node, i.e. the [method _enter_tree] callback of a parent node will be triggered before its child's.
		Once all nodes have been added in the scene tree, they receive the NOTIFICATION_READY notification and their respective [method _ready] callbacks are triggered. For groups of nodes, the [method _ready] callback is called in reverse order, from the children up to the parent nodes.
		It means that when adding a scene to the scene tree, the following order will be used for the callbacks: [method _enter_tree] of the parent, [method _enter_tree] of the children, [method _ready] of the children and finally [method _ready] of the parent (and that recursively for the whole scene).
		[b]Processing:[/b] Nodes can be set to the "process" state, so that they receive a callback on each frame requesting them to process (do something). Normal processing (callback [method _process], toggled with [method set_process]) happens as fast as possible and is dependent on the frame rate, so the processing time [i]delta[/i] is variable. Fixed processing (callback [method _fixed_process], toggled with [method set_fixed_process]) happens a fixed amount of times per second (by default 60) and is useful to link itself to the physics.
		Nodes can also process input events. When set, the [method _input] function will be called for each input that the program receives. In many cases, this can be overkill (unless used for simple projects), and the [method _unhandled_input] function might be preferred; it is called when the input event was not handled by anyone else (typically, GUI [Control] nodes), ensuring that the node only receives the events that were meant for it.
		To keep track of the scene hierarchy (especially when instancing scenes into other scenes), an "owner" can be set for the node with [method set_owner]. This keeps track of who instanced what. This is mostly useful when writing editors and tools, though.
		Finally, when a node is freed with [method free] or [method queue_free], it will also free all its children.
		[b]Networking with nodes:[/b] After connecting to a server (or making one, see [NetworkedMultiplayerENet]) it is possible to use the built-in RPC (remote procedure call) system to easily communicate over the network. By calling [method rpc] with a method name, it will be called locally, and in all connected peers (peers = clients and the server that accepts connections), with behaviour varying depending on the network mode ([method set_network_mode]) on the receiving peer. To identify which [Node] receives the RPC call Godot will use its [NodePath] (make sure node names are the same on all peers).

methods.name: _enter_tree
methods.description:
Called when the node enters the [SceneTree] (e.g. upon instancing, scene changing or after calling [method add_child] in a script). If the node has children, its [method _enter_tree] callback will be called first, and then that of the children.
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_ENTER_TREE notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _exit_tree
methods.description:
Called when the node leaves the [SceneTree] (e.g. upon freeing, scene changing or after calling [method remove_child] in a script). If the node has children, its [method _exit_tree] callback will be called last, after all its children have left the tree.
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_EXIT_TREE notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _fixed_process
methods.description:
Called during the fixed processing step of the main loop. Fixed processing means that the frame rate is synced to the physics, i.e. the [code]delta[/code] variable should be constant.
				It is only called if fixed processing has been enabled with [method set_fixed_process].
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_FIXED_PROCESS notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _process
methods.description:
Called during the processing step of the main loop. Processing happens at every frame and as fast as possible, so the [code]delta[/code] time since the previous frame is not constant.
				It is only called if processing has been enabled with [method set_process].
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_PROCESS notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: _ready
methods.description:
Called when the node is "ready", i.e. when both the node and its children have entered the scene tree. If the node has children, their [method _ready] callback gets triggered first, and the node will receive the ready notification only afterwards.
				Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_READY notification in [method Object._notification].

methods.name: add_child
methods.description:
Add a child [Node]. Nodes can have as many children as they want, but every child must have a unique name. Children nodes are automatically deleted when the parent node is deleted, so deleting a whole scene is performed by deleting its topmost node.
				The optional boolean argument enforces creating child nodes with human-readable names, based on the name of the node being instanced instead of its type only.

methods.name: add_to_group
methods.description: Add a node to a group. Groups are helpers to name and organize a subset of nodes, like for example "enemies" or "collectables". A [Node] can be in any number of groups. Nodes can be assigned a group at any time, but will not be added to it until they are inside the scene tree (see [method is_inside_tree]).

methods.name: can_process
methods.description: Return true if the node can process, i.e. whether its pause mode allows processing while the scene tree is paused (see [method set_pause_mode]). Always returns true if the scene tree is not paused, and false if the node is not in the tree. FIXME: Why FAIL_COND?

methods.name: duplicate
methods.description:
Duplicate the node, returning a new [Node].
				You can fine-tune the behavior using the [code]flags[/code], which are based on the DUPLICATE_* constants.

methods.name: find_node
methods.description: Find a descendant of this node whose name matches [code]mask[/code] as in [method String.match] (i.e. case sensitive, but '*' matches zero or more characters and '?' matches any single character except '.'). Note that it does not match against the full path, just against individual node names.

methods.name: get_child
methods.description: Return a child node by its index (see [method get_child_count]). This method is often used for iterating all children of a node.

methods.name: get_child_count
methods.description: Return the amount of child nodes.

methods.name: get_children
methods.description: Return an array of references ([Node]) to the child nodes.

methods.name: get_filename
methods.description: Return a filename that may be contained by the node. When a scene is instanced from a file, it topmost node contains the filename from where it was loaded (see [method set_filename]).

methods.name: get_fixed_process_delta_time
methods.description: Return the time elapsed since the last fixed frame (see [method _fixed_process]). This is always the same in fixed processing unless the frames per second is changed in [OS].

methods.name: get_groups
methods.description: Return an array listing the groups that the node is part of.

methods.name: get_index
methods.description: Get the node index, i.e. its position among the siblings of its parent.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Return the name of the node. This name is unique among the siblings (other child nodes from the same parent).

methods.name: get_node
methods.description:
Fetch a node. The [NodePath] must be valid (or else an error will be raised) and can be either the path to child node, a relative path (from the current node to another node), or an absolute path to a node.
				Note: fetching absolute paths only works when the node is inside the scene tree (see [method is_inside_tree]).
				[i]Example:[/i] Assume your current node is Character and the following tree:
				[codeblock]
				/root
				/root/Character
				/root/Character/Sword
				/root/Character/Backpack/Dagger
				/root/MyGame
				/root/Swamp/Alligator
				/root/Swamp/Mosquito
				/root/Swamp/Goblin
				[/codeblock]
				Possible paths are:
				[codeblock]
				get_node("Sword")
				get_node("Backpack/Dagger")
				get_node("../Swamp/Alligator")
				get_node("/root/MyGame")
				[/codeblock]

methods.name: get_owner
methods.description: Get the node owner (see [method set_owner]).

methods.name: get_parent
methods.description: Return the parent node of the current node, or an empty [Node] if the node lacks a parent.

methods.name: get_path
methods.description: Return the absolute path of the current node. This only works if the current node is inside the scene tree (see [method is_inside_tree]).

methods.name: get_path_to
methods.description: Return the relative path from the current node to the specified node in "node" argument. Both nodes must be in the same scene, or else the function will fail.

methods.name: get_process_delta_time
methods.description: Return the time elapsed (in seconds) since the last process callback. This is almost always different each time.

methods.name: is_a_parent_of
methods.description: Return [i]true[/i] if the "node" argument is a direct or indirect child of the current node, otherwise return [i]false[/i].

methods.name: is_fixed_processing
methods.description: Return true if fixed processing is enabled (see [method set_fixed_process]).

methods.name: is_greater_than
methods.description: Return [i]true[/i] if "node" occurs later in the scene hierarchy than the current node, otherwise return [i]false[/i].

methods.name: is_processing
methods.description: Return whether processing is enabled in the current node (see [method set_process]).

methods.name: is_processing_input
methods.description: Return true if the node is processing input (see [method set_process_input]).

methods.name: is_processing_unhandled_input
methods.description: Return true if the node is processing unhandled input (see [method set_process_unhandled_input]).

methods.name: move_child
methods.description: Move a child node to a different position (order) amongst the other children. Since calls, signals, etc are performed by tree order, changing the order of children nodes may be useful.

methods.name: print_tree
methods.description: Print the scene to stdout. Used mainly for debugging purposes.

methods.name: propagate_notification
methods.description: Notify the current node and all its children recursively by calling notification() in all of them.

methods.name: raise
methods.description: Move this node to the top of the array of nodes of the parent node. This is often useful on GUIs ([Control]), because their order of drawing fully depends on their order in the tree.

methods.name: remove_and_skip
methods.description: Remove a node and set all its children as children of the parent node (if exists). All even subscriptions that pass by the removed node will be unsubscribed.

methods.name: remove_child
methods.description: Remove a child [Node]. Node is NOT deleted and will have to be deleted manually.

methods.name: remove_from_group
methods.description: Remove a node from a group.

methods.name: replace_by
methods.description: Replace a node in a scene by a given one. Subscriptions that pass through this node will be lost.

methods.name: rpc
methods.description: Send a remote procedure call request to all peers on the network (and locally), optionally sending additional data as arguments. Call request will be received by nodes with the same [NodePath].

methods.name: rpc_config
methods.description: Change the method's RPC mode (one of RPC_MODE_* constants).

methods.name: rpc_id
methods.description: Send a [method rpc] to a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i].

methods.name: rpc_unreliable
methods.description: Send a [method rpc] using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: rpc_unreliable_id
methods.description: Send a [method rpc] to a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i] using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: rset
methods.description: Remotely change property's value on other peers (and locally).

methods.name: rset_config
methods.description: Change the property's RPC mode (one of RPC_MODE_* constants).

methods.name: rset_id
methods.description: Remotely change property's value on a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i].

methods.name: rset_unreliable
methods.description: Remotely change property's value on other peers (and locally) using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: rset_unreliable_id
methods.description: Remotely change property's value on a specific peer identified by [i]peer_id[/i] using an unreliable protocol.

methods.name: set_filename
methods.description: A node can contain a filename. This filename should not be changed by the user, unless writing editors and tools. When a scene is instanced from a file, it topmost node contains the filename from where it was loaded.

methods.name: set_fixed_process
methods.description: Enables or disables node fixed framerate processing. When a node is being processed, it will receive a NOTIFICATION_PROCESS at a fixed (usually 60 fps, check [OS] to change that) interval (and the [method _fixed_process] callback will be called if exists). It is common to check how much time was elapsed since the previous frame by calling [method get_fixed_process_delta_time].

methods.name: set_name
methods.description: Set the name of the [Node]. Name must be unique within parent, and setting an already existing name will cause for the node to be automatically renamed.

methods.name: set_owner
methods.description: Set the node owner. A node can have any other node as owner (as long as a valid parent, grandparent, etc ascending in the tree). When saving a node (using SceneSaver) all the nodes it owns will be saved with it. This allows to create complex SceneTrees, with instancing and subinstancing.

methods.name: set_process
methods.description: Enables or disables node processing. When a node is being processed, it will receive a NOTIFICATION_PROCESS on every drawn frame (and the [method _process] callback will be called if exists). It is common to check how much time was elapsed since the previous frame by calling [method get_process_delta_time].

methods.name: set_process_input
methods.description: Enable input processing for node. This is not required for GUI controls! It hooks up the node to receive all input (see [method _input]).

methods.name: set_process_unhandled_input
methods.description: Enable unhandled input processing for node. This is not required for GUI controls! It hooks up the node to receive all input that was not previously handled before (usually by a [Control]). (see [method _unhandled_input]).

signals.name: renamed
signals.description: Emitted when the node is renamed.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PROCESS
constants.description: Notification received every frame when the process flag is set (see [method set_process]).

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PARENTED
constants.description: Notification received when a node is set as a child of another node. Note that this doesn't mean that a node entered the Scene Tree.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_UNPARENTED
constants.description: Notification received when a node is unparented (parent removed it from the list of children).

Node2D.name: Node2D
Node2D.description: Base node for 2D system. Node2D contains a position, rotation and scale, which is used to position and animate. It can alternatively be used with a custom 2D transform ([Transform2D]). A tree of Node2Ds allows complex hierarchies for animation and positioning.

methods.name: edit_set_pivot
methods.description: Set the pivot position of the 2D node to 'pivot' value. This method is implemented only in some nodes that inherit Node2D.

methods.name: get_angle_to
methods.description: Return the rotation angle in radians needed for the 2d node to point at 'point' position.

methods.name: get_global_position
methods.description: Return the global position of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_global_rotation
methods.description: Return the global rotation in radians of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_global_rotation_in_degrees
methods.description: Return the global rotation in degrees of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_global_scale
methods.description: Return the global scale of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_position
methods.description: Return the position of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_relative_transform_to_parent
methods.description: Return the transform [Transform2D] calculated relatively to the parent of this 2D node.

methods.name: get_rotation
methods.description: Return the rotation in radians of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_rotation_in_degrees
methods.description: Return the rotation in degrees of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_scale
methods.description: Return the scale of the 2D node.

methods.name: get_z
methods.description: Return the Z-index of the 2D node.

methods.name: global_translate
methods.description: Apply a global translation of 'offset' to the 2D node, starting from its current global position.

methods.name: is_z_relative
methods.description: Return true if the Z-index value of this 2D node is relative to its parent's. Else, return false.

methods.name: look_at
methods.description: Rotate the 2d node so it points at 'point' position.

methods.name: move_local_x
methods.description: Apply a local translation on X axis to the 2D node according to the 'delta' of the process. If 'scaled' is false, the movement is normalized.

methods.name: move_local_y
methods.description: Apply a local translation on Y axis to the 2D node according to the 'delta' of the process. If 'scaled' is false, the movement is normalized.

methods.name: rotate
methods.description: Apply a rotation (in radians) to the 2D node, starting from its current rotation.

methods.name: scale
methods.description: Apply the 'ratio' scale to the 2D node, according to its current scale value.

methods.name: set_global_position
methods.description: Set the global position of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_global_rotation
methods.description: Set the global rotation in radians of the 2D node

methods.name: set_global_rotation_in_degrees
methods.description: Set the global rotation in degrees of the 2D node

methods.name: set_global_scale
methods.description: Set the global scale of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_global_transform
methods.description: Set the global transform [Transform2D] of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_position
methods.description: Set the position of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_rotation
methods.description: Set the rotation in radians of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_rotation_in_degrees
methods.description: Set the rotation in degrees of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_scale
methods.description: Set the scale of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_transform
methods.description: Set the local transform [Transform2D] of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_z
methods.description: Set the Z-index value of the 2D node.

methods.name: set_z_as_relative
methods.description: Set the Z-index value as relative to the parent node of this 2D node. Thus, if this 2D node's Z-index value is 2 and its parent's effective Z-index is 3, then the effective Z-index value of this 2D node would be 3 + 2 = 5.

methods.name: translate
methods.description: Apply a local translation of 'offset' to the 2D node, starting from its current local position.

NodePath.name: NodePath
NodePath.description:
A pre-parsed relative or absolute path in a scene tree, for use with [method Node.get_node] and similar functions. It can reference a node, a resource within a node, or a property of a node or resource. For instance, [code]"Path2D/PathFollow2D/Sprite:texture:size"[/code] would refer to the size property of the texture resource on the node named "Sprite" which is a child of the other named nodes in the path. Note that if you want to get a resource, you must end the path with a colon, otherwise the last element will be used as a property name.
		You will usually just pass a string to [method Node.get_node] and it will be automatically converted, but you may occasionally want to parse a path ahead of time with [NodePath] or the literal syntax [code]@"path"[/code]. Exporting a [NodePath] variable will give you a node selection widget in the properties panel of the editor, which can often be useful.
		A [NodePath] is made up of a list of node names, a list of "subnode" (resource) names, and the name of a property in the final node or resource.

methods.name: NodePath
methods.description: Create a NodePath from a string, e.g. "Path2D/PathFollow2D/Sprite:texture:size". A path is absolute if it starts with a slash. Absolute paths are only valid in the global scene tree, not within individual scenes. In a relative path, [code]"."[/code] and [code]".."[/code] indicate the current node and its parent.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Get the node name indicated by [code]idx[/code] (0 to [method get_name_count])

methods.name: get_name_count
methods.description: Get the number of node names which make up the path.

methods.name: get_property
methods.description: Get the path's property name, or an empty string if the path doesn't have a property.

methods.name: get_subname
methods.description: Get the resource name indicated by [code]idx[/code] (0 to [method get_subname_count])

methods.name: get_subname_count
methods.description: Get the number of resource names in the path.

methods.name: is_absolute
methods.description: Return true if the node path is absolute (not relative).

methods.name: is_empty
methods.description: Return true if the node path is empty.

OS.name: OS
OS.description: Operating System functions. OS Wraps the most common functionality to communicate with the host Operating System, such as: mouse grabbing, mouse cursors, clipboard, video mode, date and time, timers, environment variables, execution of binaries, command line, etc.

methods.name: alert
methods.description: Displays a modal dialog box utilizing the host OS.

methods.name: can_draw
methods.description: Return true if the host OS allows drawing.

methods.name: can_use_threads
methods.description: Returns if the current host platform is using multiple threads.

methods.name: delay_msec
methods.description: Delay executing of the current thread by given milliseconds.

methods.name: delay_usec
methods.description: Delay executing of the current thread by given microseconds.

methods.name: dump_memory_to_file
methods.description:
Dumps the memory allocation ringlist to a file (only works in debug).
				Entry format per line: "Address - Size - Description"

methods.name: dump_resources_to_file
methods.description:
Dumps all used resources to file (only works in debug).
				Entry format per line: "Resource Type : Resource Location"
				At the end of the file is a statistic of all used Resource Types.

methods.name: execute
methods.description: Execute the binary file in given path, optionally blocking until it returns. A process ID is returned.

methods.name: find_scancode_from_string
methods.description: Returns the scancode of the given string (e.g. "Escape")

methods.name: get_borderless_window
methods.description: Returns true if the current window is borderless.

methods.name: get_clipboard
methods.description: Get clipboard from the host OS.

methods.name: get_cmdline_args
methods.description: Return the commandline passed to the engine.

methods.name: get_current_screen
methods.description: Returns the current screen index (0 padded).

methods.name: get_data_dir
methods.description: Return the absolute directory path of user data path([user://]).

methods.name: get_date
methods.description: Returns current date as a dictionary of keys: year, month, day, weekday, dst (daylight savings time).

methods.name: get_datetime
methods.description: Returns current datetime as a dictionary of keys: year, month, day, weekday, dst (daylight savings time), hour, minute, second.

methods.name: get_datetime_from_unix_time
methods.description:
Get a dictionary of time values when given epoch time.
				Dictionary Time values will be a union of values from [method get_time] and [method get_date] dictionaries (with the exception of dst = day light standard time, as it cannot be determined from epoch).

methods.name: get_dynamic_memory_usage
methods.description: Return the total amount of dynamic memory used (only works in debug).

methods.name: get_environment
methods.description: Return an environment variable.

methods.name: get_executable_path
methods.description: Return the path to the current engine executable.

methods.name: get_latin_keyboard_variant
methods.description:
Returns the current latin keyboard variant as a String.
				Possible return values are: "QWERTY", "AZERTY", "QZERTY", "DVORAK", "NEO" or "ERROR"

methods.name: get_locale
methods.description: Return the host OS locale.

methods.name: get_model_name
methods.description: Returns the model name of the current device.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Return the name of the host OS. Possible values are: "Android", "Haiku", "iOS", "HTML5", "OSX", "Server", "Windows", "UWP", "X11".

methods.name: get_process_ID
methods.description: Returns the game process ID

methods.name: get_processor_count
methods.description: Returns the number of cores available in the host machine.

methods.name: get_scancode_string
methods.description: Returns the given scancode as a string (e.g. Return values: "Escape", "Shift+Escape").

methods.name: get_screen_count
methods.description: Returns the number of displays attached to the host machine

methods.name: get_screen_dpi
methods.description:
Returns the dots per inch density of the specified screen.

				On Android Devices, the actual screen densities are grouped into six generalized densities:
					ldpi    - 120 dpi
					mdpi    - 160 dpi
					hdpi    - 240 dpi
					xhdpi   - 320 dpi
					xxhdpi  - 480 dpi
					xxxhdpi - 640 dpi

methods.name: get_screen_orientation
methods.description: Returns the current screen orientation, the return value will be one of the SCREEN_ORIENTATION constants in this class.

methods.name: get_screen_size
methods.description: Returns the dimensions in pixels of the specified screen.

methods.name: get_static_memory_peak_usage
methods.description: Return the max amount of static memory used (only works in debug).

methods.name: get_ticks_msec
methods.description: Return the amount of time passed in milliseconds since the engine started.

methods.name: get_time
methods.description: Returns current time as a dictionary of keys: hour, minute, second

methods.name: get_unix_time
methods.description: Return	the current unix timestamp.

methods.name: get_unix_time_from_datetime
methods.description:
Get an epoch time value from a dictionary of time values.
				[code]datetime[/code] must be populated with the following keys: year, month, day, hour, minute, second.
				You can pass the output from [method get_datetime_from_unix_time] directly into this function. Daylight savings time (dst), if present, is ignored.

methods.name: get_window_position
methods.description: Returns the window position relative to the screen, the origin is the top left corner, +Y axis goes to the bottom and +X axis goes to the right.

methods.name: get_window_size
methods.description: Returns the size of the window (without counting window manager decorations).

methods.name: has_environment
methods.description: Return true if an environment variable exists.

methods.name: has_virtual_keyboard
methods.description: Returns true if the platform has a virtual keyboard, false otherwise.

methods.name: hide_virtual_keyboard
methods.description: Hides the virtual keyboard if it is shown, does nothing otherwise.

methods.name: is_in_low_processor_usage_mode
methods.description: Return true if low cpu usage mode is enabled.

methods.name: is_keep_screen_on
methods.description: Returns whether the screen is being kept on or not.

methods.name: is_stdout_verbose
methods.description: Return true if the engine was executed with -v (verbose stdout).

methods.name: is_window_fullscreen
methods.description: Returns whether the window is in fullscreen mode or not.

methods.name: is_window_maximized
methods.description: Return true if the window is maximized.

methods.name: is_window_minimized
methods.description: Return true if the window is minimized.

methods.name: is_window_resizable
methods.description: Returns whether the window is resizable or not.

methods.name: kill
methods.description: Kill a process ID (this method can be used to kill processes that were not spawned by the game).

methods.name: request_attention
methods.description: Request the user attention to the window. It'll flash the taskbar button on Windows or bounce the dock icon on OSX.

methods.name: set_clipboard
methods.description: Set clipboard to the OS.

methods.name: set_keep_screen_on
methods.description: Set keep screen on if true, or goes to sleep by device setting if false. (for Android/iOS)

methods.name: set_low_processor_usage_mode
methods.description: Set to true to enable the low cpu usage mode. In this mode, the screen only redraws when there are changes, and a considerable sleep time is inserted between frames. This way, editors using the engine UI only use very little cpu.

methods.name: set_screen_orientation
methods.description: Sets the current screen orientation, the argument value must be one of the SCREEN_ORIENTATION constants in this class.

methods.name: set_window_fullscreen
methods.description: Sets window fullscreen mode to the [i]enabled[/i] argument, [i]enabled[/i] is a toggle for the fullscreen mode, calling the function with [i]enabled[/i] true when the screen is not on fullscreen mode will cause the screen to go to fullscreen mode, calling the function with [i]enabled[/i] false when the screen is in fullscreen mode will cause the window to exit the fullscreen mode.

methods.name: set_window_maximized
methods.description: Set the window size to maximized.

methods.name: set_window_minimized
methods.description: Set whether the window is minimized.

methods.name: set_window_position
methods.description: Sets the position of the window to the specified position (this function could be restricted by the window manager, meaning that there could be some unreachable areas of the screen).

methods.name: set_window_resizable
methods.description: Set the window resizable state, if the window is not resizable it will preserve the dimensions specified in the project settings.

methods.name: set_window_size
methods.description: Sets the window size to the specified size.

methods.name: set_window_title
methods.description: Sets the window title to the specified string.

methods.name: show_virtual_keyboard
methods.description: Shows the virtual keyboard if the platform has one. The [i]existing_text[/i] parameter is useful for implementing your own LineEdit, as it tells the virtual keyboard what text has already been typed (the virtual keyboard uses it for auto-correct and predictions).

Object.name: Object
Object.brief_description: Base class for all non built-in types.
Object.description:
Base class for all non built-in types. Everything not a built-in type starts the inheritance chain from this class.
		Objects do not manage memory, if inheriting from one the object will most likely have to be deleted manually (call the [method free] function from the script or delete from C++).
		Some derivates add memory management, such as [Reference] (which keeps a reference count and deletes itself automatically when no longer referenced) and [Node], which deletes the children tree when deleted.
		Objects export properties, which are mainly useful for storage and editing, but not really so much in programming. Properties are exported in [method _get_property_list] and handled in [method _get] and [method _set]. However, scripting languages and C++ have simpler means to export them.
		Objects also receive notifications ([method _notification]). Notifications are a simple way to notify the object about simple events, so they can all be handled together.

methods.name: XL_MESSAGE
methods.description: Deprecated, will go away.

methods.name: _get
methods.description: Return a property, return null if the property does not exist.

methods.name: _get_property_list
methods.description: Return the property list, array of dictionaries, dictionaries must contain: name:String, type:int (see TYPE_* enum in [@Global Scope]) and optionally: hint:int (see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@Global Scope]), hint_string:String, usage:int (see PROPERTY_USAGE_* in [@Global Scope]).

methods.name: _notification
methods.description: Notification request, the notification id is received.

methods.name: _set
methods.description: Set a property. Return true if the property was found.

methods.name: add_user_signal
methods.description: Add a user signal (can be added anytime). Arguments are optional, but can be added as an array of dictionaries, each containing "name" and "type" (from [@Global Scope] TYPE_*).

methods.name: can_translate_messages
methods.description: Return true if this object can translate strings.

methods.name: connect
methods.description: Connect a signal to a method at a target (member function). Binds are optional and are passed as extra arguments to the call. Flags specify optional deferred or one shot connections, see enum CONNECT_*. A signal can only be connected once to a method, and it will throw an error if already connected. If you want to avoid this, use [method is_connected] to check.

methods.name: disconnect
methods.description: Disconnect a signal from a method.

methods.name: get
methods.description: Get a property from the object.

methods.name: get_class
methods.description: Return the class of the object as a string.

methods.name: get_incoming_connections
methods.description:
Returns an [Array] of dictionaries with informations about signals that are connected to this object.
				Inside each [Dictionary] there are 3 fields:
				- "source" is a reference to signal emitter.
				- "signal_name" is name of connected signal.
				- "method_name" is a name of method to which signal is connected.

methods.name: get_instance_ID
methods.description: Return the instance ID. All objects have a unique instance ID.

methods.name: get_meta
methods.description: Return a metadata from the object.

methods.name: get_meta_list
methods.description: Return the list of metadata in the object.

methods.name: get_property_list
methods.description: Return the list of properties as an array of dictionaries, dictionaries contain: name:String, type:int (see TYPE_* enum in [@Global Scope]) and optionally: hint:int (see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@Global Scope]), hint_string:String, usage:int (see PROPERTY_USAGE_* in [@Global Scope]).

methods.name: get_script
methods.description: Return the object script (or null if it doesn't have one).

methods.name: get_signal_list
methods.description: Return the list of signals as an array of dictionaries.

methods.name: has_meta
methods.description: Return true if a metadata is found with the requested name.

methods.name: is_blocking_signals
methods.description: Return true if signal emission blocking is enabled.

methods.name: is_class
methods.description: Check the class of the object against a string (including inheritance).

methods.name: is_connected
methods.description: Return true if a connection exists for a given signal and target/method.

methods.name: notification
methods.description: Notify the object of something.

methods.name: set
methods.description: Set property into the object.

methods.name: set_block_signals
methods.description: If set to true, signal emission is blocked.

methods.name: set_message_translation
methods.description: Set true if this object can translate strings (in calls to tr() ). Default is true.

methods.name: set_meta
methods.description: Set a metadata into the object. Metadata is serialized. Metadata can be [i]anything[/i].

methods.name: set_script
methods.description: Set a script into the object, scripts extend the object functionality.

methods.name: tr
methods.description: Translate a message. Only works in message translation is enabled (which is by default). See [method set_message_translation].

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_POSTINITIALIZE
constants.description: Called right when the object is initialized. Not available in script.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PREDELETE
constants.description: Called before the object is about to be deleted.

constants.name: CONNECT_DEFERRED
constants.description: Connect a signal in deferred mode. This way, signal emissions are stored in a queue, then set on idle time.

constants.name: CONNECT_PERSIST
constants.description: Persisting connections are saved when the object is serialized to file.

constants.name: CONNECT_ONESHOT
constants.description: One shot connections disconnect themselves after emission.

OmniLight.name: OmniLight
OmniLight.brief_description: OmniDirectional Light, such as a light bulb or a candle.
OmniLight.description: An OmniDirectional light is a type of [Light] node that emits lights in all directions. The light is attenuated through the distance and this attenuation can be configured by changing the energy, radius and attenuation parameters of [Light].

OptionButton.name: OptionButton
OptionButton.brief_description: Button control that provides selectable options when pressed.
OptionButton.description: OptionButton is a type button that provides a selectable list of items when pressed. The item selected becomes the "current" item and is displayed as the button text.

methods.name: add_icon_item
methods.description: Add an item, with a "texture" icon, text "label" and (optionally) id. If no "id" is passed, "id" becomes the item index. New items are appended at the end.

methods.name: add_item
methods.description: Add an item, with text "label" and (optionally) id. If no "id" is passed, "id" becomes the item index. New items are appended at the end.

methods.name: add_separator
methods.description: Add a separator to the list of items. Separators help to group items. Separator also takes up an index and is appended at the end.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear all the items in the [OptionButton].

methods.name: get_item_ID
methods.description: Return the ID of the item at index "idx".

methods.name: get_item_count
methods.description: Return the amount of items in the OptionButton.

methods.name: get_item_icon
methods.description: Return the icon of the item at index "idx".

methods.name: get_item_text
methods.description: Return the text of the item at index "idx".

methods.name: get_selected
methods.description: Return the current item index

methods.name: select
methods.description: Select an item by index and make it the current item.

methods.name: set_item_ID
methods.description: Set the ID of an item at index "idx".

methods.name: set_item_icon
methods.description: Set the icon of an item at index "idx".

methods.name: set_item_text
methods.description: Set the text of an item at index "idx".

signals.name: item_selected
signals.description: This signal is emitted when the current item was changed by the user. ID of the item selected is passed as argument (if no IDs were added, ID will be just the item index).

PHashTranslation.name: PHashTranslation
PHashTranslation.description: Optimized translation. Uses real-time compressed translations, which results in very small dictionaries.

PackedScene.name: PackedScene
PackedScene.description: TODO: explain ownership, and that node does not need to own itself

methods.name: pack
methods.description: Pack will ignore any sub-nodes not owned by given node. See [method Node.set_owner].

PacketPeer.name: PacketPeer
PacketPeer.brief_description: Abstraction and base class for packet-based protocols.
PacketPeer.description: PacketPeer is an abstraction and base class for packet-based protocols (such as UDP). It provides an API for sending and receiving packets both as raw data or variables. This makes it easy to transfer data over a protocol, without having to encode data as low level bytes or having to worry about network ordering.

methods.name: get_available_packet_count
methods.description: Return the number of packets currently available in the ring-buffer.

methods.name: get_packet
methods.description: Get a raw packet.

methods.name: get_packet_error
methods.description: Return the error state of the last packet received (via [method get_packet] and [method get_var]).

methods.name: get_var
methods.description: Get a Variant.

methods.name: put_packet
methods.description: Send a raw packet.

methods.name: put_var
methods.description: Send a Variant as a packet.

PacketPeerStream.name: PacketPeerStream
PacketPeerStream.brief_description: Wrapper to use a PacketPeer over a StreamPeer.
PacketPeerStream.description: PacketStreamPeer provides a wrapper for working using packets over a stream. This allows for using packet based code with StreamPeers. PacketPeerStream implements a custom protocol over the StreamPeer, so the user should not read or write to the wrapped StreamPeer directly.

methods.name: set_stream_peer
methods.description: Set the StreamPeer object to be wrapped

PacketPeerUDP.name: PacketPeerUDP
PacketPeerUDP.description: UDP packet peer. Can be used to send raw UDP packets as well as [Variant]\ s.

methods.name: close
methods.description: Close the UDP socket the [PacketPeerUDP] is currently listening on.

methods.name: get_packet_ip
methods.description: Return the IP of the remote peer that sent the last packet(that was received with [method get_packet] or [method get_var]).

methods.name: get_packet_port
methods.description: Return the port of the remote peer that sent the last packet(that was received with [method get_packet] or [method get_var]).

methods.name: is_listening
methods.description: Return whether this [PacketPeerUDP] is listening.

methods.name: listen
methods.description:
Make this [PacketPeerUDP] listen on the "port" binding to "bind_address" with a buffer size "recv_buf_size".
				If "bind_address" is set as "*" (default), the peer will listen on all available addresses (both IPv4 and IPv6).
				If "bind_address" is set as "0.0.0.0" (for IPv4) or "::" (for IPv6), the peer will listen on all available addresses matching that IP type.
				If "bind_address" is set to any valid address (e.g. "192.168.1.101", "::1", etc), the peer will only listen on the interface with that addresses (or fail if no interface with the given address exists).

methods.name: set_dest_address
methods.description: Set the destination address and port for sending packets and variables, a hostname will be resolved using if valid.

methods.name: wait
methods.description: Wait for a packet to arrive on the listening port, see [method listen].

Panel.name: Panel
Panel.brief_description: Provides an opaque background for [Control] children.
Panel.description: Panel is a [Control] that displays an opaque background. It's commonly used as a parent and container for other types of [Control] nodes.

PanelContainer.name: PanelContainer
PanelContainer.description: Panel container type. This container fits controls inside of the delimited area of a stylebox. It's useful for giving controls an outline.

ParallaxBackground.name: ParallaxBackground
ParallaxBackground.brief_description: A node used to create a parallax scrolling background.
ParallaxBackground.description: A ParallaxBackground will use one or more [ParallaxLayer] nodes to create a parallax scrolling background. Each [ParallaxLayer] can be set to move at different speeds relative to the camera movement, this can be used to create an illusion of depth in a 2D game.

methods.name: get_limit_begin
methods.description: Return the beginning limit.

methods.name: get_limit_end
methods.description: Return the ending limit.

methods.name: get_scroll_base_offset
methods.description: Return the base offset.

methods.name: get_scroll_base_scale
methods.description: Return the base motion scale.

methods.name: is_ignore_camera_zoom
methods.description: Return ignoring camera zoom.

methods.name: set_ignore_camera_zoom
methods.description: Set to true for all child [ParallaxLayer] nodes to not be affected by the zoom level of the camera.

methods.name: set_limit_begin
methods.description: Set the left and top limits in pixels for scrolling to begin. If the camera is outside of this limit the background will not continue to scroll. If an axis is greater than or equal to the corresponding axis of limit_end, then it will not limit scrolling for that axis.

methods.name: set_limit_end
methods.description: Set the right and bottom limits in pixels for scrolling to end. If the camera is outside of this limit the background will not continue to scroll. If an axis is less than or equal to the corresponding axis of limit_begin, then it will not limit scrolling for that axis.

methods.name: set_scroll_base_offset
methods.description: Set the base offset in pixels of all children [ParallaxLayer] nodes.

methods.name: set_scroll_base_scale
methods.description: Set the base motion scale of all children [ParallaxLayer] nodes.

ParallaxLayer.name: ParallaxLayer
ParallaxLayer.brief_description: A parallax scrolling layer to be used with [ParallaxBackground].
ParallaxLayer.description: A ParallaxLayer must be the child of a [ParallaxBackground] node. All child nodes will be affected by the parallax scrolling of this layer.

methods.name: get_mirroring
methods.description: Return the mirroring of the ParallaxLayer.

methods.name: get_motion_scale
methods.description: Return the motion scale of the ParallaxLayer.

methods.name: set_mirroring
methods.description: Set the mirroring of the ParallaxLayer. If an axis is set to 0 then that axis will have no mirroring.

methods.name: set_motion_scale
methods.description: Set the motion scale of the ParallaxLayer. If an axis is set to 0 then it will not move at all, it will stick with the camera.

Particles2D.name: Particles2D
Particles2D.description: Particles2D is a particle system 2D [Node] that is used to simulate several types of particle effects, such as explosions, rain, snow, fireflies, or other magical-like shinny sparkles. Particles are drawn using impostors, and given their dynamic behavior, the user must provide a visibility bounding box (although helpers to create one automatically exist).

methods.name: get_amount
methods.description: Returns the amount of particles spawned at each emission

methods.name: get_lifetime
methods.description: Gets the amount of seconds that each particle will be visible.

methods.name: get_texture
methods.description: Returns the texture for emitted particles

methods.name: is_emitting
methods.description: Returns whether this emitter is currently emitting or not

methods.name: set_amount
methods.description: Sets the amount of particles spawned at each emission

methods.name: set_emitting
methods.description: If this is set to true then the particle emitter will emit particles, if its false it will not.

methods.name: set_lifetime
methods.description: Sets the amount of seconds that each particle will be visible.

Path.name: Path
Path.description: This class is a container/Node-ification of a [Curve3D], so it can have [Spatial] properties and [Node] info.

methods.name: get_curve
methods.description: Returns the [Curve3D] contained.

methods.name: set_curve
methods.description: Sets the [Curve3D].

Path2D.name: Path2D
Path2D.description: This class is a container/Node-ification of a [Curve2D], so it can have [Node2D] properties and [Node] info.

methods.name: get_curve
methods.description: Returns the [Curve2D] contained.

methods.name: set_curve
methods.description: Sets the [Curve2D].

PathFollow.name: PathFollow
PathFollow.description:
This node takes its parent [Path], and returns the coordinates of a point within it, given a distance from the first vertex.
		It is useful for making other nodes follow a path, without coding the movement pattern. For that, the nodes must be descendants of this node. Then, when setting an offset in this node, the descendant nodes will move accordingly.

methods.name: get_cubic_interpolation
methods.description: This method returns whether the position between two cached points (see [method set_cubic_interpolation]) is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: get_h_offset
methods.description: Returns the X displacement this node has from its parent [Path].

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path in 3D units.

methods.name: get_rotation_mode
methods.description: Returns the rotation mode. The constants below list which axes are allowed to rotate for each mode.

methods.name: get_unit_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path as a number in the range 0.0 (for the first vertex) to 1.0 (for the last).

methods.name: get_v_offset
methods.description: Returns the Y displacement this node has from its parent [Path].

methods.name: has_loop
methods.description: Returns whether this node wraps its offsets around, or truncates them to the path ends.

methods.name: set_cubic_interpolation
methods.description:
The points along the [Curve3D] of the [Path] are precomputed before use, for faster calculations. The point at the requested offset is then calculated interpolating between two adjacent cached points. This may present a problem if the curve makes sharp turns, as the cached points may not follow the curve closely enough.
				There are two answers to this problem: Either increase the number of cached points and increase memory consumption, or make a cubic interpolation between two points at the cost of (slightly) slower calculations.
				This method controls whether the position between two cached points is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: set_h_offset
methods.description:
Moves this node in the X axis. As this node's position will be set every time its offset is set, this allows many PathFollow to share the same curve (and thus the same movement pattern), yet not return the same position for a given path offset.
				A similar effect may be achieved moving the this node's descendants.

methods.name: set_loop
methods.description: If set, any offset outside the path's length (whether set by [method set_offset] or [method set_unit_offset] will wrap around, instead of stopping at the ends. Set it for cyclic paths.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, measured in 3D units along the path. This sets this node's position to a point within the path.

methods.name: set_rotation_mode
methods.description: Allows or forbids rotation on one or more axes, per the constants below.

methods.name: set_unit_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, considering 0.0 as the first vertex and 1.0 as the last. This is just another way of expressing the offset within the path, as the offset supplied is multiplied internally by the path's length.

methods.name: set_v_offset
methods.description: Moves this node in the Y axis, for the same reasons of [method set_h_offset].

constants.name: ROTATION_Y
constants.description: Allows the PathFollow to rotate in the Y axis only.

constants.name: ROTATION_XY
constants.description: Allows the PathFollow to rotate in both the X, and Y axes.

constants.name: ROTATION_XYZ
constants.description: Allows the PathFollow to rotate in any axis.

PathFollow2D.name: PathFollow2D
PathFollow2D.description:
This node takes its parent [Path2D], and returns the coordinates of a point within it, given a distance from the first vertex.
		It is useful for making other nodes follow a path, without coding the movement pattern. For that, the nodes must be descendants of this node. Then, when setting an offset in this node, the descendant nodes will move accordingly.

methods.name: get_cubic_interpolation
methods.description: This method returns whether the position between two cached points (see [method set_cubic_interpolation]) is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: get_h_offset
methods.description: Returns the horizontal displacement this node has from its parent [Path2D].

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path in pixels.

methods.name: get_unit_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path as a number in the range 0.0 (for the first vertex) to 1.0 (for the last).

methods.name: get_v_offset
methods.description: Returns the vertical displacement this node has from its parent [Path2D].

methods.name: has_loop
methods.description: Returns whether this node wraps its offsets around, or truncates them to the path ends.

methods.name: is_rotating
methods.description: Returns whether this node rotates to follow the path.

methods.name: set_cubic_interpolation
methods.description:
The points along the [Curve2D] of the [Path2D] are precomputed before use, for faster calculations. The point at the requested offset is then calculated interpolating between two adjacent cached points. This may present a problem if the curve makes sharp turns, as the cached points may not follow the curve closely enough.
				There are two answers to this problem: Either increase the number of cached points and increase memory consumption, or make a cubic interpolation between two points at the cost of (slightly) slower calculations.
				This method controls whether the position between two cached points is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: set_h_offset
methods.description:
Moves this node horizontally. As this node's position will be set every time its offset is set, this allows many PathFollow2D to share the same curve (and thus the same movement pattern), yet not return the same position for a given path offset.
				A similar effect may be achieved moving this node's descendants.

methods.name: set_loop
methods.description: If set, any offset outside the path's length (whether set by [method set_offset] or [method set_unit_offset] will wrap around, instead of stopping at the ends. Set it for cyclic paths.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, measured in pixels along the path. This sets this node's position to a point within the path.

methods.name: set_rotate
methods.description: If set, this node rotates to follow the path, making its descendants rotate.

methods.name: set_unit_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, considering 0.0 as the first vertex and 1.0 as the last. This is just another way of expressing the offset within the path, as the offset supplied is multiplied internally by the path's length.

methods.name: set_v_offset
methods.description: Moves the PathFollow2D vertically, for the same reasons of [method set_h_offset].

Physics2DDirectBodyState.name: Physics2DDirectBodyState
Physics2DDirectBodyState.brief_description: Direct access object to a physics body in the [Physics2DServer].
Physics2DDirectBodyState.description: Direct access object to a physics body in the [Physics2DServer]. This object is passed via the direct state callback of rigid/character bodies, and is intended for changing the direct state of that body.

methods.name: get_angular_velocity
methods.description: Return the angular velocity of the body.

methods.name: get_contact_collider
methods.description: Return the [RID] of the collider.

methods.name: get_contact_collider_id
methods.description: Return the object id of the collider.

methods.name: get_contact_collider_object
methods.description: Return the collider object, this depends on how it was created (will return a scene node if such was used to create it).

methods.name: get_contact_collider_pos
methods.description: Return the contact position in the collider.

methods.name: get_contact_collider_shape
methods.description: Return the collider shape index.

methods.name: get_contact_collider_shape_metadata
methods.description: Return the metadata of the collided shape. This metadata is different from [method Object.get_meta], and is set with [method Physics2DServer.shape_set_data].

methods.name: get_contact_collider_velocity_at_pos
methods.description: Return the linear velocity vector at contact point of the collider.

methods.name: get_contact_count
methods.description: Return the amount of contacts this body has with other bodies. Note that by default this returns 0 unless bodies are configured to log contacts.

methods.name: get_contact_local_normal
methods.description: Return the local normal (of this body) of the contact point.

methods.name: get_contact_local_pos
methods.description: Return the local position (of this body) of the contact point.

methods.name: get_contact_local_shape
methods.description: Return the local shape index of the collision.

methods.name: get_inverse_inertia
methods.description: Return the inverse of the inertia of the body.

methods.name: get_inverse_mass
methods.description: Return the inverse of the mass of the body.

methods.name: get_linear_velocity
methods.description: Return the current linear velocity of the body.

methods.name: get_space_state
methods.description: Return the current state of space, useful for queries.

methods.name: get_step
methods.description: Return the timestep (delta) used for the simulation.

methods.name: get_total_angular_damp
methods.description: Return the rate at which the body stops rotating, if there are not any other forces moving it.

methods.name: get_total_gravity
methods.description: Return the total gravity vector being currently applied to this body.

methods.name: get_total_linear_damp
methods.description: Return the rate at which the body stops moving, if there are not any other forces moving it.

methods.name: get_transform
methods.description: Return the transform matrix of the body.
